 International|ODI]]\n| matches2 = 99\n| runs2 = 588\n| bat avg2 = 18.96\n| 100s/50s2 = 0/1\n| top score2 = 69\n| deliveries2 = 4,851\n| wickets2 = 143\n| bowl avg2 = 31.79\n| fivefor2 = 2\n| tenfor2 = n/a\n| best bowling2 = 5/27\n| catches/stumpings2 = 30/\u2013\n| column3 = [[First-class cricket|FC]]\n| matches3 = 175\n| runs3 = 6,822\n| bat avg3 = 32.48\n| 100s/50s3 = 10/37\n| top score3 = 180\n| deliveries3 = 29,901\n| wickets3 = 512\n| bowl avg3 = 35.05\n| fivefor3 = 20\n| tenfor3 = 1\n| best bowling3 = 7/107\n| catches/stumpings3 = 79/\u2013\n| column4 = [[List A cricket|LA]]\n| matches4 = 217\n| runs4 = 1,709\n| bat avg4 = 19.20\n| 100s/50s4 = 0/2\n| top score4 = 71\n| deliveries4 = 9,968\n| wickets4 = 289\n| bowl avg4 = 31.28\n| fivefor4 = 3\n| tenfor4 = n/a\n| best bowling4 = 5/27\n| catches/stumpings4 = 69/\u2013\n| date = 16 February 2020\n| source = http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/player/244497.html Cricinfo\n}}\n'''Adil Usman Rashid''' (born 17 February 1988) is an English cricketer who plays for [[Yorkshire County Cricket Club|Yorkshire]] and [[England cricket team|England]] as a [[leg spin]]ner. Rashid was part of the England squad that won the [[2019 Cricket World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/cricket/england-cricket-world-cup-player-ratings-how-every-star-fared-on-the-road-to-glory-a4189706.html |title=England Cricket World Cup player ratings: How every star fared on the road to glory |work=Evening Standard |accessdate=15 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nPreviously a player with [[England Under-19 cricket team|England Under-19s]], in December 2008, he was called into the full [[England national cricket team|England]] [[Test cricket|Test]] squad, for the [[England cricket team in India in 2008-09|Test matches to be played in India]]. He was then selected for the full tour of the West Indies. He made his Test debut on 13 October 2015 [[English cricket team against Pakistan in the UAE in 2015\u201316|against Pakistan in the UAE]].<ref name=\"Test\">{{cite news |title=England tour of United Arab Emirates, 1st Test: England v Pakistan at Abu Dhabi, Oct 13-17, 2015 |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/902635.html |work=ESPNcricinfo |publisher=ESPN Sports Media |date=13 October 2015 |accessdate=13 October 2015 }}</ref> As a leg spinner, Rashid received coaching from [[Terry Jenner]] as part of an [[England and Wales Cricket Board|ECB]] programme to encourage wrist-spinners.<ref name=\"ECB profile\">{{cite web|url = http://www.ecb.co.uk/stats/player-profiles/biography?id=3899&name=adil-rashid|title = Adil Rashid|accessdate = 11 June 2015|publisher = [[England and Wales Cricket Board|ECB]]|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150611213503/http://www.ecb.co.uk/stats/player-profiles/biography?id=3899&name=adil-rashid|archivedate = 11 June 2015|url-status = dead|df = dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nRashid is only the third Yorkshire-born Asian to play first-team cricket for Yorkshire,<ref>\n{{cite news|first=Lyles |last=Christopher |title=Rashid leads way for Yorkshire Asians |url=http://observer.guardian.co.uk/sport/story/0,,1827135,00.html |work=[[The Observer]] |publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited |date=23 July 2006 |accessdate=12 May 2007 |quote=For the record, Ismail Dawood, who was born in Dewsbury, made his championship debut for Yorkshire in 2004, having already represented three other counties, while Ajmal Shahzad, then 18, played one-day cricket for the first team in the same season. |location=London |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070602103910/http://observer.guardian.co.uk/sport/story/0%2C%2C1827135%2C00.html |archivedate=2 June 2007 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n<!--Note that the Guardian article says that Rashid is the second Yorkshire-born Asian to play in a *Championship* game - Shahzad did not do that, but nevertheless played first-*team* cricket-->\nand the first of [[Pakistan]]i origin.<ref name=\"ECB profile\" /> In 2006, ECB bowling coach [[David Parsons (cricket coach)|David Parsons]] considered him the most talented young leg-spinner in the country.<ref name=\"Spinning into the spotlight\">{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/256072.html |title=Spinning into the spotlight |accessdate=12 May 2007 |last=McGlashan |first=Andrew |date=9 August 2006 |publisher=[[Cricinfo]]}}</ref>\n\nRashid has been described as a strong asset for England in ODIs by English skipper [[Eoin Morgan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.cricbuzz.com/cricket-news/106900/fortunate-to-win-high-scoring-game-eoin-morgan-england-cricket-jos-buttler|title=Rashid is a strong asset for England:Morgan|work=Cricbuzz|access-date=28 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nRashid was born in [[Bradford]], [[West Yorkshire]], and is of [[Pakistani]] background.<ref name=\"ECB profile\" /> Like his England teammate [[Moeen Ali]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/cricket/moeen-ali-interview-the-england-star-on-backing-alastair-cook-boos-in-birmingham-and-wearing-save-9793027.html|title=Moeen Ali interview: The England star on backing Alastair Cook, boos in Birmingham and wearing Save Gaza wristbands|work=Evening Standard|date=14 October 2014|accessdate=18 October 2015}}</ref> he belongs to the [[British Mirpuris|Mirpuri community]], his family having migrated to England in 1967 from [[Pakistani Occupied Kashmir]] Better know as POK<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/columnists/scyldberry/2342493/Yorkshire-slowly-skittles-its-traditional-mould.html|title=Yorkshire slowly skittles its traditional mould|work=The Telegraph|date=6 August 2006|accessdate=18 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nHis brothers Haroon and [[Amar Rashid|Amar]] are also cricketers.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/sport/1628275.Brothers_hoping_to_join_the_county_set/ | title=Brothers hoping to join the county set | date=19 August 2007 | first=Bill | last=Marshall | newspaper=Bradford Telegraph and Argus | accessdate=13 March 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Early career==\n\n===Early promise===\nRashid showed promise from a young age: Jenner spotted him as a 14-year-old,<ref name=\"Spinning into the spotlight\" /> and, in early July 2005, aged 17, he took 6\u201313 for Yorkshire's Academy (youth) team.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://cricketarchive.co.uk/Archive/Scorecards/82/82850.html | title=Sheffield United v Yorkshire Academy in 2005 | accessdate=12 May 2007 | publisher=CricketArchive}}</ref> A few days later he hit 111 for Yorkshire Cricket Board Under-17s against their Cheshire equivalents in the Under-17s County Championship.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://cricketarchive.co.uk/Archive/Scorecards/82/82889.html | title=Yorkshire Cricket Board Under-17s v Cheshire Cricket Board Under-17s in 2005 | accessdate=12 May 2007 | publisher=CricketArchive}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, he played a number of games for Yorkshire Second XI, making four successive [[century (cricket)|centuries]].<ref name=\"Spinning into the spotlight\" />\nThis form, combined with a calf injury to [[Darren Lehmann]],\nearned him the chance to make his [[first-class cricket|first-class]] debut.\n\n===2006: County debut and youth Tests===\nRashid made his county cricket debut against [[Warwickshire County Cricket Club|Warwickshire]] at [[North Marine Road]], [[Scarborough, North Yorkshire|Scarborough]], as a replacement for injured overseas batsman [[Darren Lehmann]]. In the second innings he bowled a magnificent 6/67 to rip through Warwickshire's middle order and win the match for Yorkshire.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://cricketarchive.co.uk/Archive/Scorecards/85/85803.html | title= Yorkshire v Warwickshire in 2006 | accessdate=12 May 2007 | publisher=CricketArchive}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket/content/story/254122.html|title=Debutant Rashid spins Yorkshire fine victory {{!}} Cricket|date=21 July 2006|access-date=13 October 2008|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8052/scorecard/225042/yorkshire-vs-birmingham-bears-county-championship-division-one-2006|title=County Championship Division One at Scarborough, Jul 19-21 2006 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> Rashid was then included in the [[England Under-19 cricket team|England Under-19s]] Test squad for their series against [[India Under-19 cricket team|India Under-19s]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/251578.html|title=Chopra handed Under-19 captaincy {{!}} Cricket|date=27 June 2006|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> Making his debut for the side in the first Test at [[St Lawrence Ground|Canterbury]], he scored 13 and 23 runs and took one wicket.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/engine/match/239927.html | title=England Under-19s v India Under-19s at Canterbury, Jul 26\u201329, 2006| accessdate=12 May 2007 | publisher=[[Cricinfo]]}}</ref><!--The opening line of his ECB profile says he was called up for the *second* Test; this is clearly wrong, as Rashid's appearance on the first Test scoreboard proves, and indeed the correct \"first Test\" is used lower down the same ECB article!--> In the second Test, at [[County Ground, Taunton|Taunton]], he produced a dominant all-round display, scoring 114 and 48 and claiming 8/157 and 2/45.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/engine/match/239928.html | title=England Under-19s v India Under-19s at Taunton, Aug 1\u20134, 2006 | accessdate=12 May 2007 | publisher=[[Cricinfo]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/255457.html|title=Rashid leads England fightback {{!}} Cricket|date=2 August 2006|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/255527.html|title=Rashid's allround heroics give England the edge {{!}} Cricket|date=3 August 2006|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/255620.html|title=Rashid and Chopra star again in stalemate {{!}} Cricket|date=4 August 2006|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/14595/scorecard/239928/england-under-19s-vs-india-under-19s-2nd-youth-test-india-under-19s-tour-of-england-2006|title=2nd Youth Test, India Under-19s tour of England at Taunton, Aug 1-4 2006 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> He also played in the third Test at the Denis Compton Oval in [[Shenley, Hertfordshire|Shenley]], but made less of an impression, only taking three wickets and scoring 15 and 12 runs.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/engine/match/239929.html | title=England Under-19s v India Under-19s at Shenley, Aug 6\u20139, 2006 | accessdate=12 May 2007 | publisher=[[Cricinfo]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/14595/scorecard/239929/england-under-19s-vs-india-under-19s-3rd-youth-test-india-under-19s-tour-of-england-2006|title=3rd Youth Test, India Under-19s tour of England at Shenley, Aug 6-9 2006 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nFrom mid-August until the end of the season, he held down a regular spot in the Yorkshire side.<ref name=\"Player Oracle\">{{cite web | url=http://cricketarchive.co.uk/cgi-bin/ask_the_player_oracle.cgi?playernumber=88341 | title=Player Oracle | accessdate=12 May 2007 | publisher=CricketArchive}}</ref> He continued to impress, taking 4/96 against [[Middlesex County Cricket Club|Middlesex]] at Scarborough<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket/content/story/258360.html|title=Goodwin blasts century for Sussex {{!}} Cricket|date=1 September 2006|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8052/scorecard/225060/yorkshire-vs-middlesex-county-championship-division-one-2006|title=County Championship Division One at Scarborough, Aug 30 - Sep 2 2006 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> and scoring 63, his maiden first-class half-century, against [[Nottinghamshire County Cricket Club|Nottinghamshire]] at [[Headingley Stadium|Headingley]] as part of a fourth-wicket stand of 130 with [[Craig White]] to dig Yorkshire out of a hole from 42/3 before helping to bowl out Nottinghamshire's tail to win the match for Yorkshire.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://cricketarchive.co.uk/Archive/Scorecards/86/86060.html | title=Yorkshire v Nottinghamshire in 2006 | accessdate=12 May 2007 | publisher=CricketArchive}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket/content/story/259514.html|title=Lancashire frustrated by plodding Durham {{!}} Cricket|date=13 September 2006|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket/content/story/259758.html|title=Cork special boost Lancashire {{!}} Cricket|date=16 September 2006|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8052/scorecard/225067/yorkshire-vs-nottinghamshire-county-championship-division-one-2006|title=County Championship Division One at Leeds, Sep 13-16 2006 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> Rashid also featured in a two-day \"spin match\" held by the [[England and Wales Cricket Board]], a programme which would simulate different match-based scenarios to develop young spin bowlers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/258416.html|title=Youngsters set for 'spin match' {{!}} Cricket|date=2 September 2006|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\n===2007: Young Player of the Year===\nDuring the winter, Rashid suffered from a [[stress fracture]] in his back<ref name=\"ECB profile\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket/content/story/273887.html|title=Rashid on the mend {{!}} Cricket|date=25 December 2006|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> and missed England Under-19s' tour of Malaysia, but he recovered well enough to be picked for the 2006\u201307 [[England A cricket team|England A]] tour of Bangladesh.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/274842.html|title=Yardy handed England A captaincy {{!}} Cricket|date=2 January 2007|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> Despite unimpressive performances, he was tipped by Yorkshire teammate [[Jason Gillespie]] to play international cricket for England in the future.<ref name=gillespie>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/284948.html|title=Gillespie tips Rashid for international stardom {{!}} Cricket|date=12 March 2007|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote|text=Adil is probably the best young cricketer in England ... I think he could play an allround role for England in the future.|author=[[Jason Gillespie]]<ref name=gillespie/>}}\n\nRashid started the English summer at [[Lord's]], playing for [[Marylebone Cricket Club]] (MCC) against the 2006 champion county, [[Sussex County Cricket Club|Sussex]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://cricketarchive.co.uk/Archive/Scorecards/107/107653.html | title=Marylebone Cricket Club v Sussex in 2007 | accessdate=12 May 2007 | publisher=CricketArchive}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/288679.html|title=Harmison and Hoggard lead MCC attack {{!}} Cricket|date=5 April 2007|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> In his [[County Championship]] game of the season, at [[The Oval]] against [[Surrey County Cricket Club|Surrey]] a few days later, he hit 86 in the first innings, putting on 190 with [[Jacques Rudolph]] for the sixth wicket.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://cricketarchive.co.uk/Archive/Scorecards/107/107662.html | title=Surrey v Yorkshire in 2007 | accessdate=12 May 2007 | publisher=CricketArchive}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2007/content/story/291279.html|title=Sussex start defence in style {{!}} Cricket|date=18 April 2007|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8052/scorecard/268048/surrey-vs-yorkshire-county-championship-division-one-2007|title=County Championship Division One at London, Apr 18-21 2007 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> This established a new partnership record for the sixth wicket for Yorkshire against Surrey, surpassing a mark that had stood since 1902.<ref>{{cite news|first=David|last=Warner|title=Bowler leads glut of batting records in breathtaking start for Yorkshire regime|url=http://www.yorkshireccc.com/reportscards/lvchampionship2007/asurryork|publisher=[[Yorkshire County Cricket Club]]|accessdate=12 May 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070515042559/http://www.yorkshireccc.com/reportscards/lvchampionship2007/asurryork|archivedate=15 May 2007|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> At the end of April he continued to impress with bowling figures of 5/88 against [[Durham County Cricket Club|Durham]] at Headingley.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://cricketarchive.co.uk/Archive/Scorecards/107/107675.html | title=Yorkshire v Durham in 2007 | accessdate=12 May 2007 | publisher=CricketArchive}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2007/content/story/292328.html|title=Rashid continues to impress|date=25 April 2007|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8052/scorecard/268054/yorkshire-vs-durham-county-championship-division-one-2007|title=County Championship Division One at Leeds, Apr 25-27 2007 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> Due to his form he was picked to play for [[England Lions (cricket team)|England Lions]] in a tour match against [[India national cricket team|India]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/14366/scorecard/275786/england-lions-vs-india-tour-match-india-tour-of-ireland-england-and-scotland-2007|title=Tour Match, India tour of Ireland, England and Scotland at Chelmsford, Jul 13-15 2007 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nRashid was considered to play for England's Under-19 side again in their series against [[Pakistan Under-19 cricket team|Pakistan]], but his Yorkshire coach [[Martyn Moxon]] showed displeasure at the idea of Rashid being pulled away from county cricket. The selectors decided that as Rashid had progressed to the next level of cricket, having appeared for England Lions, and therefore he shouldn't be pulled out of county cricket to play for England Under-19s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/303055.html|title=Rashid withdrawn from Under-19 series {{!}} Cricket|date=21 July 2007|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/303622.html|title=Hamilton-Brown defends Under-19 cricket {{!}} Cricket|last=Thompson|first=Jenny|date=25 July 2007|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> In continuing to play county cricket, he scored his maiden first-class century, 108 against [[Worcestershire County Cricket Club|Worcestershire]] at Kidderminster,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/303622.html|title=Batty guides Surrey to the draw {{!}} Cricket|date=16 August 2007|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2007/content/story/307215.html|title=Declaration and Ali burst bring game to life {{!}} Cricket|last=Ward|first=John|date=16 August 2007|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2007/content/story/307289.html|title=Smith guides Worcestershire run chase {{!}} Cricket|last=Ward|first=John|date=17 August 2007|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8052/scorecard/268101/worcestershire-vs-yorkshire-county-championship-division-one-2007|title=County Championship Division One at Kidderminster, Aug 14-17 2007 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> and another half-century against [[Warwickshire County Cricket Club|Warwickshire]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2007/content/story/308056.html|title=Rudolph double flays Warwickshire {{!}} Cricket|last=Ward|first=John|date=23 August 2007|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8052/scorecard/268105/yorkshire-vs-birmingham-bears-county-championship-division-one-2007|title=County Championship Division One at Scarborough, Aug 22-24 2007 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nOver the course of the 2007 English cricket season, Rashid scored 837 with a batting average of 44.05 and took 43 wickets with a bowling average of 42.16 across all first-class matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/88/88341/f_Batting_by_Season.html|title=First-class Batting and Fielding in Each Season by Adil Rashid|access-date=13 October 2018|work=CricketArchive|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/88/88341/f_Bowling_by_Season.html|title=First-class Bowling in Each Season by Adil Rashid|access-date=13 October 2018|work=CricketArchive}}</ref> He took the most wickets of any Yorkshire player and scored the fourth-most runs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/averages/batting_bowling_by_team.html?id=2991;team=1515;type=tournament|title=Cricket Records {{!}} Records {{!}} County Championship Division One, 2007 - Yorkshire {{!}} {{!}} Batting and bowling averages|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> He won several awards in 2007 for his strong form. In June 2007 he won both the YCCSA Young Player of the Year Award for 2006<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yorkshireccc.com/news/copy_of_news716202446 |title=Latest Cricket News &#124; YCCC News |publisher=Yorkshireccc.com |accessdate=24 February 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928000526/http://www.yorkshireccc.com/news/copy_of_news716202446 |archivedate=28 September 2007 }}</ref> and the Neil Lloyd Young Cricketer of the Year Award for 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yorkshireccc.com/news/news716202446 |title=Latest Cricket News &#124; YCCC News |publisher=Yorkshireccc.com |accessdate=24 February 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928000625/http://www.yorkshireccc.com/news/news716202446 |archivedate=28 September 2007 }}</ref> On 9 September Rashid was named 2007 [[Cricket Writers' Club Young Cricketer of the Year]], while on 24 September he was awarded the title of [[PCA Young Player of the Year]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ecb.co.uk/domestic/gibson-reaps-top-award,15154,EN.html |title=Gibson lands top award |accessdate=25 September 2007 |publisher=[[England and Wales Cricket Board|ECB]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071118093405/http://ecb.co.uk/domestic/gibson-reaps-top-award%2C15154%2CEN.html |archivedate=18 November 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/312374.html|title=Gibson picks up PCA's Most Valuable Player award {{!}} Cricket|date=24 September 2007|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2007, Rashid was named in the \"England Performance Programme squad\", to train at home and in India during the 2007\u201308 winter.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/7030274.stm | work=BBC News | title=Broad named in development squad | date=5 October 2007 | accessdate=23 April 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/313831.html|title=England name strong performance squad {{!}} Cricket|date=5 October 2007|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\n===2008: First tour with national team===\n{{See also|English cricket team in the West Indies in 2008\u201309}}\nIn January 2008, Rashid was named in the England Lions squad for the [[2007\u201308 Duleep Trophy]] in India.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/328905.html|title=Prior dropped as Ambrose gets his chance {{!}} Cricket|date=4 January 2008|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> He played two games for the tournament and took six wickets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/averages/batting_bowling_by_team.html?id=3434;team=1003;type=tournament|title=Cricket Records {{!}} Records {{!}} Duleep Trophy, 2007/08 - England Lions {{!}} {{!}} Batting and bowling averages|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> For the second season in a row he was also named in the Marylebone Cricket Club squad to play against the champion county, this time [[Sussex County Cricket Club|Sussex]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2008/content/story/344588.html|title=Sussex to face strong MCC outfit {{!}} Cricket|date=31 March 2008|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/345730.html|title=Sussex primed for season curtain-raise {{!}} Cricket|date=9 April 2008|access-date=14 October 2008|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> He also retained his place in the England Performance Programme squad.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/7358539.stm | work=BBC News | title=England selectors look at Rashid | date=21 April 2008 | accessdate=23 April 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/story/347210.html|title=Key given hope of England recall {{!}} Cricket|date=21 April 2008|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nThere was concern early in the season that Rashid's bowling was losing some of its variety as it seemed his batting was taking precedence,<ref name=topoftheclass>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/magazine/content/story/371053.html |title=Top of the class |publisher=Cricinfo.com |author=Andrew McGlashan |date=25 September 2008 |postscript=<!--None-->}} Retrieved on 4 December 2008.</ref> but he then took career-best bowling figures of 7/107 against [[Hampshire County Cricket Club|Hampshire]] at the [[Rose Bowl, Hampshire|Rose Bowl]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2008/content/story/364023.html|title=Durham sense victory after 23 wickets fall {{!}} Cricket|date=7 August 2008|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8052/scorecard/319925/hampshire-vs-yorkshire-county-championship-division-one-2008|title=County Championship Division One at Southampton, Aug 6-8 2008 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> He followed this up with hauls of 5/95 against [[Lancashire County Cricket Club|Lancashire]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2008/content/story/364804.html|title=Croft holds up Yorkshire's progress {{!}} Cricket|last=Ward|first=John|date=13 August 2008|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2008/content/story/365018.html|title=Gale and McGrath grind down Lancashire {{!}} Cricket|last=Ward|first=John|date=14 August 2008|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8052/scorecard/319927/lancashire-vs-yorkshire-county-championship-division-one-2008|title=County Championship Division One at Manchester, Aug 12-15 2008 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> and 7/136 against [[Sussex County Cricket Club|Sussex]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2008/content/story/371420.html|title=Goodwin and Rashid bask in the sun {{!}} Cricket|last=Williamson|first=Martin|date=27 September 2008|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8052/scorecard/319950/sussex-vs-yorkshire-county-championship-division-one-2008|title=County Championship Division One at Brighton, Sep 24-27 2008 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> Rashid finished the season with 62 wickets, Yorkshire's leading wicket-taker for the second year in a row.<ref name=topoftheclass/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/averages/batting_bowling_by_team.html?id=3632;team=1515;type=tournament|title=Cricket Records {{!}} Records {{!}} County Championship Division One, 2008 - Yorkshire {{!}} {{!}} Batting and bowling averages|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of the year, Rashid was included in the [[England national cricket team|English national team]] for their [[English cricket team in India in 2008\u201309|tour of India]], though he wasn't expected to be any chance of playing a match for England, only being on the tour for the experience.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/indveng/content/story/381098.html|title=Amjad Khan earns call-up {{!}} Cricket|date=7 December 2008|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/7769870.stm | work=BBC News | title=England call up Khan and Rashid | date=7 December 2008 | accessdate=23 April 2010}}</ref> He was then included in England's squad for their following [[English cricket team in the West Indies in 2008\u201309|tour of the West Indies]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wiveng2009/content/story/386961.html|title=Rashid ready to take his chance {{!}} Cricket|date=19 January 2009|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> where he was part of England's team for a tour match against a [[Saint Kitts and Nevis]] team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wiveng2009/content/story/387701.html|title=Chance for Shah as England play 11 {{!}} Cricket|date=24 January 2009|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/13775/scorecard/352670/st-kitts-invitational-xi-vs-england-tour-match-england-tour-of-west-indies-2008-09|title=Tour Match, England tour of West Indies at Basseterre, Jan 25-27 2009 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> National selector [[Geoff Miller]], described Rashid's selection at the age of 20 in the following terms:\n\n{{Quote|text=Adil Rashid... is an exciting prospect for the future and his inclusion will enable us to continue to monitor his development closely as well as providing extra competition for places in the spin-bowling department.|author=[[Geoff Miller]]<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/7802062.stm | work=BBC News | title=Vaughan misses out on tour place | date=29 December 2008 | accessdate=23 April 2010}}</ref>}}\n\n==Early international call-ups==\n===2009: World Twenty20 and ODI debut===\n{{See also|2009 ICC World Twenty20|English cricket team in Ireland in 2009|Australian cricket team in England and Scotland in 2009}}\nRashid was again included in the England Lions team for a tour match against the West Indies,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/engvwi2009/content/story/400935.html|title=Bell gets Lions call and Key leads {{!}} Cricket|date=22 April 2009|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> and he had a good all-round performance, scoring 72 runs in England Lions' first innings and taking 3/66 in the West Indies' second innings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/engvwi2009/content/story/402637.html|title=England Lions hammer West Indies {{!}} Cricket|date=2 May 2009|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/13683/scorecard/383273/england-lions-vs-west-indies-tour-match-west-indies-tour-of-england-2009|title=Tour Match, West Indies tour of England at Derby, Apr 30 - May 2 2009 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> Despite not being included in Yorkshire's side for their first two [[Twenty20]] matches of the season, Rashid's form saw him called up to the national team for the [[2009 ICC World Twenty20]] as an injury replacement for [[Andrew Flintoff]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wt202009/content/story/406257.html|title=Flintoff ruled out of World Twenty20 {{!}} Cricket|last=Miller|first=Andrew|date=27 May 2009|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> In England's first warm-up match for the tournament against [[Scotland national cricket team|Scotland]], Rashid appeared nervous, but in their second warm-up match against the West Indies he appeared more settled and took 1/20 from his 4 overs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wt202009/content/story/407237.html|title=Wright and Bopara crush West Indies {{!}} Cricket|last=McGlashan|first=Andrew|date=3 June 2009|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wt202009/content/story/407237.html|title=(D/N)ICC World Twenty20 Warm-up Matches at London, Jun 3 2009 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> During the tournament itself he had impressive performances against [[Pakistan national cricket team|Pakistan]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wt202009/content/story/407237.html|title=By jove, it's a six from England {{!}} Cricket|last=Miller|first=Andrew|date=3 June 2007|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8604/scorecard/355996/england-vs-pakistan-6th-match-group-b-icc-world-twenty20-2009|title=6th Match, Group B (D/N), ICC World Twenty20 at London, Jun 7 2009 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> and the West Indies,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wt202009/content/story/409158.html|title=Mettle, experience, comebacks and bravery {{!}} Cricket|last=Miller|first=Andrew|date=15 June 2009|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8604/scorecard/356011/england-vs-west-indies-22nd-match-group-e-icc-world-twenty20-2009|title=22nd Match, Group E (D/N), ICC World Twenty20 at London, Jun 15 2009 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> and he finished the tournament with 3 wickets at an average of 31.66 and with an economy of 7.30 runs per over from his 4 matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/wt202009/engine/records/averages/batting_bowling_by_team.html?id=4162;team=1;type=tournament|title=Cricket Records {{!}} Records {{!}} ICC World Twenty20, 2009 - England {{!}} {{!}} Batting and bowling averages|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his World Twenty20 appearances, he was included in England's training squad for the [[2009 Ashes series]] against [[Australia national cricket team|Australia]], thought to be a potential replacement for the out-of-form [[Monty Panesar]], but instead of playing a warm-up game with the England XI he played with England Lions again in a tour match against Australia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/engvaus2009/content/story/410113.html|title=Vaughan and Harmison wait on training squad {{!}} Cricket|last=McGlashan|first=Andrew|date=21 June 2009|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/engvaus2009/content/story/410177.html|title=Vaughan and Harmison left out of Ashes squad {{!}} Cricket|date=22 June 2009|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/13659/scorecard/350039/england-lions-vs-australia-tour-match-australia-tour-of-england-and-scotland-2009|title=Tour Match, Australia tour of England and Scotland at Worcester, Jul 1-4 2009 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> He was left out of England's final squad for the Ashes<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/engvaus2009/content/story/412829.html|title=Onions pips Harmison for final slot {{!}} Cricket|last=Miller|first=Andrew|date=5 July 2009|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> and instead returned to playing county cricket with Yorkshire. Rashid scored his career-best 117 [[not out]] and later on helped Yorkshire to bowl [[Hampshire County Cricket Club|Hampshire]] out with figures of 5/41.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2009/content/story/419387.html|title=Nash powers Sussex to win {{!}} Cricket|date=13 August 2009|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2009/content/story/419713.html|title=Rashid five routs Hampshire {{!}} Cricket|date=14 August 2009|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8052/scorecard/382957/hampshire-vs-yorkshire-county-championship-division-one-2009|title=County Championship Division One at Basingstoke, Aug 11-14 2009 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> He then went on to better that against [[Lancashire County Cricket Club|Lancashire]], scoring an unbeaten 157 and taking 5/97 in the first innings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2009/content/story/420952.html|title=Rashid and Bopara in the runs {{!}} Cricket|date=21 August 2009|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8052/scorecard/382963/yorkshire-vs-lancashire-county-championship-division-one-2009|title=County Championship Division One at Leeds, Aug 19-22 2009 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> The feat of scoring a century and taking a five-for in a match was the third of his career; the last player to have achieved the feat twice in a season for Yorkshire was [[George Hirst]] back in 1911.<ref>{{cite web|author=Andy Wilson |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2009/aug/21/adil-rashid-yorkshire-lancashire-county-championship |title=Adil Rashid underlines potential with 136 for Yorkshire in Roses match &#124; Sport |work=The Guardian|date=21 August 2009 |accessdate=24 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nRashid made his [[One Day International]] debut for England on 27 August 2009 against [[Ireland national cricket team|Ireland]]. He scored 7 runs and had bowling figures of 1/16 in a narrow win.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/13527/scorecard/383275/ireland-vs-england-only-odi-england-tour-of-ireland-2009|title=Only ODI, England tour of Ireland at Belfast, Aug 27 2009 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> He kept his place in the side for the 1st ODI against Australia, and he was the best of England's bowlers, only conceding 37 runs from his 10 overs. He followed this up with a quickfire 31 not out from just 23 balls with the bat to almost get England across the line in a tight finish.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/engvaus2009/content/story/423493.html|title=Rashid shines but Australia hold nerve {{!}} Cricket|last=Miller|first=Andrew|date=4 September 2009|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/13659/scorecard/350043/england-vs-australia-1st-odi-australia-tour-of-england-and-scotland-2009|title=1st ODI (D/N), Australia tour of England and Scotland at London, Sep 4 2009 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> He impressed Australians [[Michael Clarke (cricketer)|Michael Clarke]] and [[James Hopes]] with his strong performance,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/engvaus2009/content/story/423605.html|title=Rashid maturity impresses Aussies {{!}} Cricket|last=Miller|first=Andrew|date=4 September 2009|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/engvaus2009/content/story/423662.html|title=Rashid's Australian connection {{!}} Cricket|last=McGlashan|first=Andrew|date=5 September 2009|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> but he was shockingly omitted from the English side for the next match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/engvaus2009/content/story/423759.html|title=England's batsmen not learning {{!}} Cricket|last=McGlashan|first=Andrew|date=6 September 2009|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> He did return for two more matches during the series, but finished with only 2 wickets at an average of 74.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/averages/batting_bowling_by_team.html?id=4287;team=1;type=series|title=Cricket Records {{!}} Records {{!}} NatWest Series [Australia in England], 2009 - England {{!}} {{!}} Batting and bowling averages|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\n===2009\u201310: South Africa and Pakistan A===\n{{See also|English cricket team in South Africa in 2009\u201310}}\nRashid completely supplanted Monty Panesar in the England side, being named as the back-up to [[Graeme Swann]] for both the Test and ODI squads in their [[English cricket team in South Africa in 2009\u201310|tour of South Africa]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/rsaveng09/content/story/428799.html|title=Harmison and Bopara miss out for South Africa tour {{!}} Cricket|date=8 October 2009|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> He played in the second Twenty20 International between the sides, but was only used for one over in which he conceded 25 runs, after which South Africa's coach [[Mickey Arthur]] criticized the English side for not showing enough faith in Rashid's ability.<ref name=EPP>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/rsaveng09/content/story/437654.html|title=Davids stars but Test candidates struggle against Gauteng|date=30 November 2009|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/13436/scorecard/387564/south-africa-vs-england-2nd-t20i-england-tour-of-south-africa-2009-10|title=2nd T20I, England tour of South Africa at Centurion, Nov 15 2009 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> Due to an injury to Swann, Rashid was brought back into the side for the 2nd ODI, but he bowled an expensive three overs, conceding 27 runs, and was dropped once Swann was fit again.<ref name=eastlondonwarmup>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/rsaveng09/content/story/438621.html|title=Anderson ruled out of England warm-up {{!}} Cricket|last=McGlashan|first=Andrew|date=8 December 2009|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/13436/scorecard/387566/south-africa-vs-england-2nd-odi-england-tour-of-south-africa-2009-10|title=2nd ODI, England tour of South Africa at Centurion, Nov 22 2009 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> He was then dropped from South Africa's ODI squad altogether for the rest of the series, instead playing four-day matches with the England Performance Programme. Meanwhile, offspinner [[James Tredwell]] remained on stand-by to potentially play, indicating that Rashid had dropped down the pecking order.<ref name=EPP/><ref name=eastlondonwarmup/> His poor form continued in the England Performance Programme matches,<ref name=EPP/> and though he re-joined the main squad ahead of the Test series he did not play in any Test matches.<ref name=eastlondonwarmup/>\n\nFollowing the poor tour for Rashid, he was left out of England's squad for their [[English cricket team in Bangladesh in 2009\u201310|tour of Bangladesh]], instead being sent to the [[United Arab Emirates]] to play for England Lions against [[Pakistan A cricket team|Pakistan A]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/445084.html|title=Time out will help Adil Rashid - Andy Flower {{!}} Cricket|date=19 January 2010|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> His time in the UAE was somewhat more successful than his time in South Africa, and he took 3/13 in the second Twenty20 against Pakistan A to secure a series win for England Lions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/448230.html|title=England Lions secure series with second win {{!}} Cricket|date=14 February 2010|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/13354/scorecard/443089/england-lions-vs-pakistan-a-2nd-match-pakistan-a-tour-of-united-arab-emirates-2009-10|title=2nd Match, Pakistan A tour of United Arab Emirates at Sharjah, Feb 14 2010 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> After the Twenty20 series against Pakistan A, England Lions also played a Twenty20 against the main England team and Rashid helped cause a shock upset win with another strong bowling performance of 3/22.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/pakveng2010/content/story/448772.html|title=Kieswetter and Lumb leads Lions victory {{!}} Cricket|date=17 February 2010|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/13344/scorecard/443095/england-vs-england-lions-tour-match-england-lions-tour-of-united-arab-emirates-2009-10|title=Tour Match (D/N), England Lions tour of United Arab Emirates at Abu Dhabi, Feb 17 2010 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\n==Continued domestic career==\n[[File:Adil Rashid sharp.jpg|thumb|right|150px|Rashid playing for Yorkshire in 2010]]\n\n===2010\u201311: Overlooked by national selectors; Big Bash===\nFollowing his unsuccessful winter abroad, Rashid returned to playing county cricket with Yorkshire in the 2010 summer. He immediately showed that he still had the potential to return to the English national team, showing his batting skills with an impressive innings against Warwickshire in his first match of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2010/content/story/455513.html|title=Yorkshire edge lead in fluctuating battle {{!}} Cricket|last=Dobell|first=George|date=10 April 2010|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8052/scorecard/435399/birmingham-bears-vs-yorkshire-county-championship-division-one-2010|title=County Championship Division One at Birmingham, Apr 9-12 2010 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> His self-confidence returned throughout the season and he had several impressive performances with both ball and bat in the county championship,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2010/content/story/460259.html|title=Lyth lights up run-glut at Taunton {{!}} Cricket|date=19 May 2010|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2010/content/story/461013.html|title=Batsmen put Yorkshire in command {{!}} Cricket|date=26 May 2010|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2010/content/story/465529.html|title=McGrath steadies Yorkshire towards a draw {{!}} Cricket|last=Culley|first=Jon|date=30 June 2010|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2010/content/story/466611.html|title=Yorkshire victory builds Championship lead {{!}} Cricket|last=Culley|first=Jon|date=8 July 2010|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2010/content/story/468335.html|title=Adam Lyth impresses but Essex retain edge {{!}} Cricket|date=21 July 2010|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2010/content/story/473981.html|title=Adil Rashid lifts Yorkshire after Dominic Cork burst {{!}} Cricket|date=24 August 2018|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> finishing the season with 732 runs at 45.75 and 57 wickets at 31.29,<ref name=201011ashes>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/the-ashes-2010-11/content/story/478475.html|title=Chris Tremlett and Monty Panesar earn Ashes calls {{!}} Cricket|last=McGlashan|first=Andrew|date=23 September 2010|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> as well as taking 26 wickets in the [[2010 Twenty20 Cup]], the most of the Yorkshire bowlers and the fourth-most overall.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=5610;type=tournament|title=Cricket Records {{!}} Records {{!}} Friends Provident t20, 2010 {{!}} {{!}} Most wickets|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> Despite his strong performances throughout the season he was still overlooked by English selectors, being left out of their home series against [[Bangladesh national cricket team|Bangladesh]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2010/content/story/466363.html|title=Adil Rashid spins Yorkshire ahead {{!}} Cricket|last=Culley|first=Jon|date=6 July 2010|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> and the squad for the [[2010\u201311 Ashes series]] in favour of Monty Panesar.<ref name=201011ashes/>\n\nNot having been selected to play for England over the 2010\u201311 winter, Rashid instead played for [[South Australia cricket team|South Australia]] in the [[2010\u201311 KFC Twenty20 Big Bash]]. He played a useful role in the team alongside fellow spinner [[Nathan Lyon]], and finished the season with 10 wickets, one behind the tournament's leaders Lyon and [[Pat Cummins]], as South Australia won the tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8627/report/461041/tasmania-vs-south-australia-twenty20-big-bash-2010-11|title=(D/N)Twenty20 Big Bash at Hobart, Jan 24 2011 {{!}} Match Report|last=Malcolm|first=Alex|date=23 January 2011|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=5899;type=tournament|title=Cricket Records {{!}} Records {{!}} Twenty20 Big Bash, 2010/11 {{!}} {{!}} Most wickets|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> Following the Big Bash, Rashid was selected to play for England Lions on a tour of the West Indies, during which they played in the local first-class competition, the [[2010\u201311 Regional Four Day Competition]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/492748.html|title=England news: Steven Finn and Ravi Bopara included in Lions squad {{!}} Cricket|date=15 December 2010|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\n===2011\u201312: Decline in form===\nRashid started the 2011 season well by taking 6/77 and 5/37 in Yorkshire's opening match against Worcestershire,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2011/content/story/510016.html|title=Worcestershire v Yorkshire: Rashid bags six on opening day {{!}} Cricket|last=Dobell|first=George|date=8 April 2011|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8052/report/492088/day/3/|title=County Championship Division One at Worcester, Apr 8-10 2011 {{!}} Match Report|last=Dobell|first=george|date=10 April 2011|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8052/scorecard/492088/worcestershire-vs-yorkshire-county-championship-division-one-2011|title=County Championship Division One at Worcester, Apr 8-10 2011 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> but overall he struggled for form, and conceded the worst bowling figures of his career, and the third-worst ever for Yorkshire, when he bowled no wicket for 187 runs against [[Sussex County Cricket Club|Sussex]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2011/content/story/517235.html|title=Sussex v Yorkshire: Murray Goodwin builds huge Sussex total {{!}} Cricket|date=30 May 2011|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8052/scorecard/492116/sussex-vs-yorkshire-county-championship-division-one-2011|title=County Championship Division One at Brighton, May 29 - Jun 1 2011 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> His poor form continued into the 2012 season, and he found himself dropped from Yorkshire's team for the first time in his county career. This came as a result of his worst ever start to a county season, taking nine wickets at 49.00 in his first six matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2012/content/story/566627.html|title=County Cricket 2012: Adil Rashid left out by Yorkshire {{!}} Cricket|last=Winter|first=Alex|date=29 May 2012|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> Yorkshire's president [[Geoffrey Boycott]] lamented that Rashid had not appeared to progress at all since he started playing county cricket, and said that Rashid needed to take responsibility for his poor performances.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2012/content/story/566751.html|title=County Cricket 2012: Adil Rashid the one to blame - Boycott|last=Hodgson|first=Myles|date=30 May 2012|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> In ten first-class matches in 2012 he took just 16 wickets at an average of 41 and made 129 runs at 16.12, his decline meaning he was no longer even asked to play for England Lions anymore.<ref name=yorkshirerift>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2013/content/story/629006.html|title=Yorkshire forced to deny Adil Rashid rift {{!}} Cricket|date=9 April 2013|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\n===2013\u201314: Return to form===\nJust hours before the start of the 2013 county season, Rashid was quoted by ''[[the Independent]]'' as saying that if his 2013 season didn't go well he'd request to go on loan from Yorkshire to a different county, which forced Yorkshire to deny that there was any rift between Rashid and the club. Martyn Moxon, then Yorkshire's director of cricket, said that the interview had been in January, months before the start of the season and that there hadn't been any issues.<ref name=yorkshirerift/> Rashid also showed that his poor form was behind him as he started the season with his highest first-class score, a 180 against [[Somerset County Cricket Club|Somerset]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2013/content/story/634592.html|title=Adil Rashid proves agreeable for Yorkshire {{!}} Cricket|last=Hopps|first=David|date=7 May 2013|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2013/content/story/634745.html|title=Adil Rashid's best continues run-scoring spree {{!}} Cricket|last=Smith|first=Les|date=8 May 2013|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8052/scorecard/593476/yorkshire-vs-somerset-county-championship-division-one-2013|title=County Championship Division One at Leeds, May 7-10 2013 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> He followed this up with two more centuries, one against Warwickshire and a second against Somerset, taking his average for the county season up to that point above 200.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2013/content/story/636498.html|title=Yorkshire breach fortress Edgbaston {{!}} Cricket|last=Hodgson|first=Myles|date=17 May 2013|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2013/content/story/638442.html|title=Marcus Trescothick offers Somerset a glimmer {{!}} Cricket|last=Tennant|first=Ivo|date=30 May 2013|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> In 2014 Rashid continued to improve his bowling, particularly in limited overs cricket, bowling career-best figures of 5/33 in a one-day match against [[Hampshire County Cricket Club|Hampshire]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2014/content/story/773089.html|title=Adil Rashid best earns Yorkshire home tie {{!}} Cricket|date=21 August 2014|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\n==Return to international cricket==\n===2014\u201315: South Africa A, West Indies and Ireland===\n{{See also|English cricket team in the West Indies in 2014\u201315|English cricket team in Ireland in 2015}}\nDue to his form in county cricket, Rashid was named in the England Lions squad for their tour of South Africa in early 2015, set to play in both their first-class and one-day series against [[South Africa A cricket team|South Africa A]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/793775.html|title=Jonathan Trott named in England Lions squad {{!}} Cricket|last=Gardner|first=Alan|date=28 October 2014|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> He batted well on the tour with innings of 78 and 68 in the unofficial Tests.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/11496/scorecard/737427/south-africa-a-vs-england-lions-1st-unofficial-test-england-lions-tour-of-south-africa-2014-15|title=1st unofficial Test, England Lions tour of South Africa at Paarl, jan 11-14 2015 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/822007.html|title=Rashid and Lyth keep Lions in the hunt {{!}} Cricket|last=Tennant|first=Ivo|date=18 January 2015|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> In March 2015, Rashid was named in the England Test squad for the [[English cricket team in the West Indies in 2014\u201315|tour of the West Indies]].<ref name=\"ENGSQUAD\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cricket/31942514|title= Jonathan Trott: England recall Warwickshire batsman|publisher=BBC Sport|date=18 March 2015|accessdate=18 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/west-indies-v-england-2015/content/story/852135.html|title=Adam Lyth, Mark Wood and Adil Rashid in Test squad {{!}} Cricket|last=Gardner|first=Alan|date=18 March 2015|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> In the tour matches leading up to England's Test series against the West Indies, Rashid did not perform well enough to get into the Test side, with the selectors favouring James Tredwell ahead of him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/west-indies-v-england-2015/content/story/861563.html|title=Moeen Ali set to replace Adil Rashid {{!}} Cricket|last=Dobell|first=George|date=14 April 2015|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> Despite not being used in the Test matches, he was not allowed to return to England to play with Yorkshire at the beginning of the county cricket season,<ref name=championship>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/871431.html|title=Moeen Ali, Adam Lyth available to play in Championship {{!}} Cricket|date=6 May 2015|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> though Rashid did leave the tour early to join England's ODI team for their [[English cricket team in Ireland in 2015|match against Ireland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/869279.html|title=Adil Rashid, Mark Wood added to squad for Ireland ODI {{!}} Cricket|date=1 May 2015|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> After the match, Yorkshire hired a private jet to fly Rashid back in time for their next county match against [[Hampshire County Cricket Club|Hampshire]], where he took four wickets in each innings.<ref name=championship/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2015/content/story/875155.html|title=Yorkshire wrap up win amid distractions {{!}} Cricket|last=Edwards|first=Paul|date=13 May 2015|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\n===2015: Return to ODI side against New Zealand and Australia===\n{{See also|New Zealand cricket team in England in 2015|Australian cricket team in England and Ireland in 2015}}\nWith the [[2015 Ashes series|2015 Ashes]] around the corner, the English selectors decided to rest Moeen Ali from [[New Zealand cricket team in England in 2015|their ODI series against New Zealand]] and brought in Rashid as his replacement.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england-v-new-zealand-2015/content/story/883659.html|title=James Anderson, Stuart Broad left out of ODI squad {{!}} Cricket|date=2 June 2015|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> Rashid had an immediate impact in the first match of the series, being involved in the [[List of One Day International cricket records#Highest partnership for each wicket|highest 7th wicket partnership of ODI history]] with [[Jos Buttler]], where they scored 177 runs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportskeeda.com/cricket/records-broken-englands-score-4089-first-odi-new-zealand|title=Records broken in England's score of 408/9 in first ODI against New Zealand|author=Dipankar Lahiri|date=9 June 2015}}</ref> Rashid reached his maiden half-century in just 37 balls and went on to score 69 runs, then he gave the most eye-catching bowling of the match as well, making use of his [[googly]] to take the wicket of [[Kane Williamson]] and finishing with figures of 4/55.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england-v-new-zealand-2015/content/story/885449.html|title=Buttler, Root hundreds set up record England win {{!}} Cricket|last=McGlashan|first=Andrew|date=9 June 2015|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> Rashid played all five matches of the series for England and finished with a total of 8 wickets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/averages/batting_bowling_by_team.html?id=9245;team=1;type=series|title=Cricket Records {{!}} Records {{!}} New Zealand in England ODI Series, 2015 - England {{!}} {{!}} Batting and bowling averages|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nRashid was included in England's 13-man squad for the first Test of the Ashes,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/the-ashes-2015/content/story/892951.html|title=Adil Rashid, Steven Finn in England Test squad {{!}} Cricket|date=1 July 2015|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> but the selectors decided that they would only use Rashid in the Test as a second spinner alongside Moeen Ali if there was a spinning pitch.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/the-ashes-2015/content/story/894429.html|title=Spinning pitch at Cardiff 'very unlikely' {{!}} Cricket|date=5 July 2015|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> Rashid remained in the Test squad for every match of the Ashes but did not play,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/the-ashes-2015/content/story/908067.html|title=James Anderson returns to squad for fifth Test {{!}} Cricket|last=McGlashan|first=Andrew|date=9 August 2015|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> and instead he continued playing county cricket for Yorkshire, scoring a century against [[Durham County Cricket Club|Durham]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2015/content/story/907961.html|title=Glenn Maxwell and Adil Rashid reassert Yorkshire dominance {{!}} Cricket|last=Edwards|first=Paul|date=8 August 2015|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> Although he had not played in the Ashes at all, Rashid did get to play in the ODI series against Australia and solidified his spot in the team with figures of 4/59 in the 1st ODI<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/the-ashes-2015/content/story/917129.html|title=Matthew Wade, bowlers put Australia 1-0 up {{!}} Cricket|last=Dobell|first=George|date=3 September 2015|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> and 2/41 in the 3rd ODI.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/the-ashes-2015/content/story/919365.html|title=Adil Rashid gives England gift of legspin {{!}} Cricket|last=McGlashan|first=Andrew|date=10 September 2015|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> Across the five-match series he took 7 wickets, the most of England's bowlers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/the-ashes-2015/engine/records/averages/batting_bowling_by_team.html?id=9255;team=1;type=series|title=Cricket Records {{!}} Records {{!}} Australia in England ODI Series, 2015 - England {{!}} {{!}} Batting and bowling averages|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\n===2015 Pakistan===\nIn October 2015, Rashid was selected in the England touring party to play [[Pakistan]] in the [[UAE]] making his debut in the First Test at [[Sheikh Zayed Cricket Stadium]]. Rashid had a torrid time in the first innings of his first match in the Test side, finishing with figures of 0-163 as Pakistan posted 523 - the worst figures by a Test debutant.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/cricket/article-3272386/Adil-Rashid-records-worst-bowling-figures-Test-debutant-0-163-England-against-Pakistan-Abu-Dhabi.html|title=Adil Rashid records worst bowling figures by Test debutant with 0-163|work=Mail Online|access-date=2018-08-13}}</ref> However, he enjoyed a remarkable turn around of fortunes in the next innings, finishing with figures of 5-64, a return that was nearly good enough for England to win the match, although it eventually finished in a draw.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/pakistan-v-england-2015-16/content/story/930075.html|title='Rashid had the character to bounce back' - Moxon|work=Cricinfo|access-date=2018-08-13|language=en}}</ref> In the second Test he took 1-84 in Pakistan's first innings and 1\u2013107 in their second as England lost the game by 178 runs, although Rashid made his maiden Test half-century in England's second innings, hitting 61.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/34635455|title=Pakistan v England: Tourists lose despite Adil Rashid rearguard|date=26 October 2015|work=BBC Sport|access-date=2018-08-13|language=en-GB}}</ref> In the third and final Test, Rashid did not take a wicket in Pakistan's first innings, and in the second innings he finished with 1-97 as England lost the match and the series 2\u20130.\n\nFollowing the Test series, Rashid played in the ODI series. He only took one wicket in the first three games, finishing with figures of 0-60 in the first game, which England lost. After taking 1-32 in the second match, he again finished wicketless in the third match of the series.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/scorecard/ECKP90174|title=Pakistan v England - Cricket|website=BBC Sport|language=en|access-date=2018-08-13}}</ref> He was expensive in the final match of the series, although he did pick up three wickets and England won the match and the series 3\u20131.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/transfer/news/12933/10064101/pakistan-v-england-batting-not-good-enough-from-tourists-says-bumble|title=Pakistan v England: Batting not good enough from tourists, says Bumble|work=SkySports|access-date=2018-08-13|language=en}}</ref>\n\nHe played in all three of the T20 matches. After not bowling or batting in the first game, he took figures of 2-18 in the second game as England secured a three run victory. He took 1-29 in the final game which went to a Super Over, with England winning the matches after the scores finished level.\n\n===2015/16 South Africa===\nAt the urging of coach [[Jason Gillespie]], Rashid signed a deal to play for [[Adelaide Strikers]] in the [[Big Bash in 2015-16]] after being left out of the England squad for the [[English cricket team in South Africa in 2015\u201316|tour of South Africa]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Steve Carroll|url=http://www.yorkpress.co.uk/sport/14094713.Adil_Rashid___quot_I_just_couldn_t_say_no_quot__to_Jason_Gillespie_and_the_Big_Bash/ |title=Adil Rashid: \"I just couldn't say no\" to Jason Gillespie and the Big Bash |publisher=[[York Press]]|date=21 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nRashid was not selected for the Test series against South Africa, although he did keep his place in the ODI side. After failing to take a wicket in the first game, he finished with figures of 1-43 in the second game which England won by five wickets. After taking 1-45 in the third game, he had his bets return of the series in the fourth match. After making 39 with the bat, he took figures of 2-38, although South Africa secured a one wicket victory. In the final match of the series he took figures of 1-59 as South Africa won the match by five wickets to win the series 3\u20132. England lost both T20 matches, although Rashid performed reasonably well, taking figures of 1-24 in the first game and 1-30 in the second game, although England lost by nine wickets.\n\n===2016 T20 World Cup===\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=October 2018}}\nRashid took figures of 1-20 in the opening game against the West Indies, although it wasn't enough to prevent a defeat. In the second game he picked up figures of 1-35 against South Africa, before taking his best figures of the tournament, 2-18 against Afghanistan. With England needing to beat Sri Lanka to qualify for the semi-finals, Rashid finished with figures of 0-31 as England won by ten runs. He did not pick up a wicket against New Zealand in the semi-final, but turned in a good performance in the final against West Indies, taking figures of 1-23. Despite his good performance, England suffered a narrow loss and finished as runners-up.\n\n===2016 Sri Lanka and Pakistan===\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=October 2018}}\nRashid did not pick up a wicket in the first ODI, although he did bowl economically as the match ended in a tie. He took 2-34 in the second match of the series, which England won by ten wickets. In the rain affected third match, he failed to pick up a wicket, and the match was eventually abandoned. In the fourth ODI he took 2-47 as England won by six wickets. He picked up another two wickets in the final game of the series as England completed a 3-0 series win after winning the match by 122 runs. Rashid played in the only T20I between the two sides, and bowled economically, conceding just 25 runs from his four overs, as England won by eight wickets.\n\nRashid took figures of 2-51 in the first ODI against Pakistan, as England got off to a winning start. In the second ODI, he took figures of 1-51 as England restricted Pakistan to 251 and won the match by four wickets. In the third match of the series he took figures of 2-73 as England again won to go 3-0 up in the series. In the fourth match he took figures of 3-47 as England won by four wickets. Rashid was rested for the final match, which England lost. He took figures of 1-29 in the only T20I between the two sides, which England lost by nine wickets.\n\n===2016 Bangladesh===\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=October 2018}}\nIn the first ODI against Bangladesh, Rashid took figures of 4-49 to help England to a 21 run victory. In the second match, he made an unbeaten 33 and took another two wickets, but England lost. In the third match of the series, he took 4-43 as England recorded a four wicket victory to win the series 2\u20131. In the first Test, Rashid scored 26 with the bat before taking 2-58. He took 1-55 in Bangladesh's second innings as England recorded a 22 run victory. In the second Test, Rashid was wicketless in the first innings but took 4-52 in the second innings. England were unable to chase down their target and lost by 108 runs.\n\n===2016-17 India===\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=October 2018}}\nIn the first Test against India, Rashid took figures of 4\u2013114 in India's first innings, before taking 3-64 in their second innings. However, England were unable to force a win and the match ended in a draw. Rashid took 2\u2013110 in India's first innings of the second Test, before making an unbeaten 32 with the bat. He continued to bowl well in India's second innings, taking 4-82, although India won the game by 246 runs. In the third Test he took figures of 4\u2013118 in India's first innings, before taking 1-28 as India secured an eight wicket victory. In the fourth Test, he took figures of 4\u2013192 in India's first innings total of 631, as they won by an innings and 36 runs. In the final match of the series, he made 60 in England's first innings before taking figures of 1-153 as India posted 759/7 and won the match to win the series 4\u20130.\n\nRashid played in the first ODI against India and took figures of 0-50 as England lost by three wickets. He did not feature in the rest of the series, although he retained his place for the T20Is. In the first T20I he did not bat or bowl as England won by seven wickets. In the second match he took 1-24 but England lost by 5 runs as India levelled the series. In the final match of the series he took figures of 0-23 as India made 202/6 and won by 75 runs.\n\nHe was also named as part of the 'Team of the Tournament' at the 2017 Champions Trophy by the ICC,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/champions-trophy/media-releases/421165|title=Live Cricket Scores & News International Cricket Council|website=www.icc-cricket.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref> Cricinfo<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/19678837/captain-sarfraz-pips-kohli-tamim-no-3|title=Champions Trophy XI: Sarfraz pips Kohli, Tamim at No. 3|website=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> and Cricbuzz.\n\n===2017 West Indies and Ireland===\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=October 2018}}\nRashid took 1-43 in the first ODI against the West Indies as England won by 45 runs. In the second match he took 2-53 as England secured a 4 wicket victory. Rashid made nine with bat as England made 328 in the final ODI, before taking 1\u20135 with the ball as England won by 186 runs to win the series 3\u20130. Later in the same year, the West Indies toured England. Rashid's first appearance was in the only T20I, in which he picked up a personal best of 3-25. He continued this good form into the ODI series, taking an economical 2-31 in the first of five, to help restrict the tourists to 204/9. England made light work of the total, as they cruised to a seven wicket victory. Despite the majority of the second ODI being abandoned due to rain, he took 3-34 in the third, while England won by 124 runs. In the final two games, Rashid picked up a solitary wicket in each, although England won both games and celebrated a 4-0 series victory as a consequence.\n\nEngland started their summer by preparing for the [[2017 ICC Champions Trophy|Champions Trophy]], which they were hosting for the second time in succession. Preparation began with two ODIs against [[Ireland cricket team|Ireland]]. In the first ODI, Rashid picked up a career best of 5-27, as Ireland stumbled to 126 all out. England won the game comfortably; they cruised to a seven wicket victory. In the second ODI, Rashid made a speedy 39 from 25 deliveries, although his bowling proved to be less effective, as he took 1-68. England still managed to win the game by 85 runs, and take a 2-0 series victory.\n\n=== 2018 Australia and India ===\n{{main|Indian cricket team in England in 2018}}\nRashid played in all five ODIs against Australia, taking 12 wickets at an average of 21.50.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/averages/batting_bowling_by_team.html?id=12028&team=1&type=series|title=Australia in England ODI Series, 2018 - England Cricket Team Records & Stats {{!}} ESPNcricinfo.com|website=Cricinfo|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2018 Rashid informed Yorkshire of his desire to only play white-ball cricket during the upcoming season, and will not feature in the [[County Championship|county championship]] for the side, preferring to focus on his limited-over career.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://yorkshireccc.com/news/view/6340/rashid-to-focus-on-white-ball-cricket|title=Rashid to focus on white ball cricket|website=Yorkshire County Cricket Club|access-date=2018-02-15}}</ref>\n\nRashid was called up to the England squad to play Test cricket against India in the 2018 series, causing controversy after his decision not to play 4-day county cricket for Yorkshire.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2018/jul/30/adil-rashid-row-alastair-cook-england-india-first-test-edgbaston|title=Adil Rashid will cope with England call-up row, insists Alastair Cook|last=Martin|first=Ali|date=30 July 2018|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-08-13}}</ref> In the second Test, he became the first England cricketer for 13 years to complete a Test match without batting, bowling or taking a catch in the field.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/sports/cricket/india-vs-england-adil-rashid-record-5304496/|title=India vs England: Adil Rashid registers absurd record|date=13 August 2018|work=The Indian Express|access-date=2018-08-13|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n===2019 West Indies and the Cricket World Cup===\nIn [[English cricket team in the West Indies in 2018-19|England's tour of West Indies in 2019]], Rashid was selected in all three squads. He played only one Test, in which his figures were 0\u2013117. In the first ODI he took 3-74, with England winning by 6 wickets. In the second, he took 1-28 in a defeat. In the fourth ODI he took his second ODI five-for, with figures of 5-85 to help England to a 28-run victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/18913/report/1158069/west-indies-vs-england-4th-odi-eng-in-wi-2018-19|title=Recent Match Report: England vs West Indies 4th ODI in Greneda, 27th February 2019|work=EspnCricinfo|accessdate=28 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, he was named in [[2019 Cricket World Cup squads#England|England's squad]] for the [[2019 Cricket World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/story/1181187.html |title=Jofra Archer misses World Cup cut but included to play Ireland, Pakistan |work=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=17 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/1183273 |title=England leave out Jofra Archer from World Cup squad |work=International Cricket Council |accessdate=17 April 2019}}</ref> On 21 June 2019, in the match against [[Sri Lanka national cricket team|Sri Lanka]], Rashid played in his 150th international match for England.<ref name=\"ARJR\">{{cite web|url=https://cricketaddictor.com/cricket/icc-cricket-world-cup-2019-match-27-england-vs-sri-lanka-stats-preview/ |title=ICC Cricket World Cup 2019 (Match 27): England vs Sri Lanka \u2013 Stats Preview |work=Cricket Addictor |accessdate=21 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Bowling style ==\nUnlike [[Shane Warne]], who relies on only one grip on most of his variations (except flipper), and adjust his speed with a slow run-up, Rashid has a quicker run-up, and relies on many grip and arm angle changes on his deliveries, and tends not to be a big turner of the ball, and tends to bowl googlies with three variations alone, which negates his lack of a true flipper, since he bowls them like a normal leg break with quicker wrist action.<ref>{{Citation|title=Leg Spin Masterclass with Shane Warne and Rashid Khan {{!}} The Big Break|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Kk1P_91DaBI|language=en|access-date=2020-01-22}}</ref>\n\n==Charity Work==\nRashid became an Ambassador for the [[Overseas Plastic Surgery Appeal]] charity in November 2018. OPSA are a Yorkshire-based charity that carry out most of their work in the Punjab region of Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web |title=Our Ambassadors \u2013 Overseas Plastic Surgery Appeal (OPSA) |url=https://opsacharity.com/ambassadors/ |website=Overseas Plastic Surgery Appeal (OPSA)}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category-inline}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{cricinfo|ref=england/content/player/244497.html}}\n* {{cricketarchive|ref=Archive/Players/88/88341/88341.html}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070429164316/http://www.yorkshireccc.com/players/capped_first_eleven/adilrashid Player Profile and Statistics : Adil Rashid] from [[Yorkshire County Cricket Club]]\n\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title= England squads \n|bg= skyblue\n|fg= #000060\n|bordercolor=#000060\n|list1=\n{{England Squad 2011 Cricket World Cup}}\n{{England Squad 2019 Cricket World Cup}}\n}}\n{{Yorkshire squad}}\n{{South Australia 2010-11 KFC Twenty20 Big Bash Champions}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rashid, Adil}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English cricketers]]\n[[Category:Yorkshire cricketers]]\n[[Category:England Test cricketers]]\n[[Category:England One Day International cricketers]]\n[[Category:England Twenty20 International cricketers]]\n[[Category:English people of Pakistani descent]]\n[[Category:Cricketers from Bradford]]\n[[Category:Cricketers at the 2011 Cricket World Cup]]\n[[Category:Cricketers who have taken five wickets on Test debut]]\n[[Category:South Australia cricketers]]\n[[Category:Marylebone Cricket Club cricketers]]\n[[Category:British Asian cricketers]]\n[[Category:English people of Mirpuri descent]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople of Pakistani descent]]\n[[Category:British sportspeople of Pakistani descent]]\n[[Category:Adelaide Strikers cricketers]]\n[[Category:Dhaka Dynamites cricketers]]\n[[Category:Cricketers at the 2019 Cricket World Cup]]\n[[Category:English cricketers of the 21st century]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English cricketer}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox cricketer\n| name = Adil Rashid\n| image = Adil Rashid (14337811452) (cropped).jpg\n| country = England\n| fullname = Adil Usman Rashid\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1988|2|17|df=yes}}\n| birth_place =[[Bradford, West Yorkshire]]\n| nickname = Dil, Dilly, Rash\n| heightft = 5\n| heightinch = 8\n| batting = Right-handed\n| bowling = [[Leg spin|Right-arm leg break]]\n| role = Bowler\n| family = [[Amar Rashid]] (brother)\n| international = true\n| internationalspan = 2009\u2013present\n| testdebutdate = 13 October\n| testdebutyear = 2015\n| testdebutagainst = Pakistan\n| testcap = 668\n| lasttestdate = 23 January\n| lasttestyear = 2019\n| lasttestagainst = West Indies\n| odidebutdate = 27 August\n| odidebutyear = 2009\n| odidebutagainst = Ireland\n| odicap = 210\n| lastodidate = 9 February\n| lastodiyear = 2020\n| lastodiagainst = South Africa\n| odishirt = 95\n| T20Idebutdate = 5 June\n| T20Idebutyear = 2009\n| T20Idebutagainst = Netherlands\n| T20Icap = 46\n| lastT20Idate = 16 February\n| lastT20Iyear = 2020\n| lastT20Iagainst = South Africa\n| T20Ishirt = 95\n| club1 = [[Yorkshire County Cricket Club|Yorkshire]]\n| year1 = {{nowrap|2006\u2013present}}\n| clubnumber1 = 3\n| club2 = [[Marylebone Cricket Club]]\n| year2 = 2007\u20132009\n| club3 = [[South Australia cricket team|South Australia]]\n| year3 = 2011\n| club4 = [[Adelaide Strikers]]\n| year4 = 2015\u20132016\n| club5 = [[T10 League|Punjabi Legends]]\n| year5 = 2017\n| club6 = [[Dhaka Dynamites]]\n| year6 = 2017\u2013present\n| columns = 4\n| column1 = [[Test cricket|Test]]\n| matches1 = 19\n| runs1 = 540\n| bat avg1 = 19.28\n| 100s/50s1 = 0/2\n| top score1 = 61\n| deliveries1 = 3,816\n| wickets1 = 60\n| bowl avg1 = 39.83\n| fivefor1 = 2\n| tenfor1 = 0\n| best bowling1 = 5/49\n| catches/stumpings1 = 4/\u2013\n| column2 = [[One Day International|ODI]]\n| matches2 = 99\n| runs2 = 588\n| bat avg2 = 18.96\n| 100s/50s2 = 0/1\n| top score2 = 69\n| deliveries2 = 4,851\n| wickets2 = 143\n| bowl avg2 = 31.79\n| fivefor2 = 2\n| tenfor2 = n/a\n| best bowling2 = 5/27\n| catches/stumpings2 = 30/\u2013\n| column3 = [[First-class cricket|FC]]\n| matches3 = 175\n| runs3 = 6,822\n| bat avg3 = 32.48\n| 100s/50s3 = 10/37\n| top score3 = 180\n| deliveries3 = 29,901\n| wickets3 = 512\n| bowl avg3 = 35.05\n| fivefor3 = 20\n| tenfor3 = 1\n| best bowling3 = 7/107\n| catches/stumpings3 = 79/\u2013\n| column4 = [[List A cricket|LA]]\n| matches4 = 217\n| runs4 = 1,709\n| bat avg4 = 19.20\n| 100s/50s4 = 0/2\n| top score4 = 71\n| deliveries4 = 9,968\n| wickets4 = 289\n| bowl avg4 = 31.28\n| fivefor4 = 3\n| tenfor4 = n/a\n| best bowling4 = 5/27\n| catches/stumpings4 = 69/\u2013\n| date = 16 February 2020\n| source = http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/player/244497.html Cricinfo\n}}\n'''Adil Usman Rashid''' (born 17 February 1988) is an English cricketer who plays for [[Yorkshire County Cricket Club|Yorkshire]] and [[England cricket team|England]] as a [[leg spin]]ner. Rashid was part of the England squad that won the [[2019 Cricket World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/cricket/england-cricket-world-cup-player-ratings-how-every-star-fared-on-the-road-to-glory-a4189706.html |title=England Cricket World Cup player ratings: How every star fared on the road to glory |work=Evening Standard |accessdate=15 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nPreviously a player with [[England Under-19 cricket team|England Under-19s]], in December 2008, he was called into the full [[England national cricket team|England]] [[Test cricket|Test]] squad, for the [[England cricket team in India in 2008-09|Test matches to be played in India]]. He was then selected for the full tour of the West Indies. He made his Test debut on 13 October 2015 [[English cricket team against Pakistan in the UAE in 2015\u201316|against Pakistan in the UAE]].<ref name=\"Test\">{{cite news |title=England tour of United Arab Emirates, 1st Test: England v Pakistan at Abu Dhabi, Oct 13-17, 2015 |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/902635.html |work=ESPNcricinfo |publisher=ESPN Sports Media |date=13 October 2015 |accessdate=13 October 2015 }}</ref> As a leg spinner, Rashid received coaching from [[Terry Jenner]] as part of an [[England and Wales Cricket Board|ECB]] programme to encourage wrist-spinners.<ref name=\"ECB profile\">{{cite web|url = http://www.ecb.co.uk/stats/player-profiles/biography?id=3899&name=adil-rashid|title = Adil Rashid|accessdate = 11 June 2015|publisher = [[England and Wales Cricket Board|ECB]]|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150611213503/http://www.ecb.co.uk/stats/player-profiles/biography?id=3899&name=adil-rashid|archivedate = 11 June 2015|url-status = dead|df = dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nRashid is only the third Yorkshire-born Asian to play first-team cricket for Yorkshire,<ref>\n{{cite news|first=Lyles |last=Christopher |title=Rashid leads way for Yorkshire Asians |url=http://observer.guardian.co.uk/sport/story/0,,1827135,00.html |work=[[The Observer]] |publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited |date=23 July 2006 |accessdate=12 May 2007 |quote=For the record, Ismail Dawood, who was born in Dewsbury, made his championship debut for Yorkshire in 2004, having already represented three other counties, while Ajmal Shahzad, then 18, played one-day cricket for the first team in the same season. |location=London |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070602103910/http://observer.guardian.co.uk/sport/story/0%2C%2C1827135%2C00.html |archivedate=2 June 2007 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n<!--Note that the Guardian article says that Rashid is the second Yorkshire-born Asian to play in a *Championship* game - Shahzad did not do that, but nevertheless played first-*team* cricket-->\nand the first of [[Pakistan]]i origin.<ref name=\"ECB profile\" /> In 2006, ECB bowling coach [[David Parsons (cricket coach)|David Parsons]] considered him the most talented young leg-spinner in the country.<ref name=\"Spinning into the spotlight\">{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/256072.html |title=Spinning into the spotlight |accessdate=12 May 2007 |last=McGlashan |first=Andrew |date=9 August 2006 |publisher=[[Cricinfo]]}}</ref>\n\nRashid has been described as a strong asset for England in ODIs by English skipper [[Eoin Morgan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.cricbuzz.com/cricket-news/106900/fortunate-to-win-high-scoring-game-eoin-morgan-england-cricket-jos-buttler|title=Rashid is a strong asset for England:Morgan|work=Cricbuzz|access-date=28 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nRashid was born in [[Bradford]], [[West Yorkshire]], and is of [[Pakistani]] background.<ref name=\"ECB profile\" /> Like his England teammate [[Moeen Ali]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/cricket/moeen-ali-interview-the-england-star-on-backing-alastair-cook-boos-in-birmingham-and-wearing-save-9793027.html|title=Moeen Ali interview: The England star on backing Alastair Cook, boos in Birmingham and wearing Save Gaza wristbands|work=Evening Standard|date=14 October 2014|accessdate=18 October 2015}}</ref> he belongs to the [[British Mirpuris|Mirpuri community]], his family having migrated to England in 1967 from [[Azad Kashmir]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/columnists/scyldberry/2342493/Yorkshire-slowly-skittles-its-traditional-mould.html|title=Yorkshire slowly skittles its traditional mould|work=The Telegraph|date=6 August 2006|accessdate=18 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nHis brothers Haroon and [[Amar Rashid|Amar]] are also cricketers.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/sport/1628275.Brothers_hoping_to_join_the_county_set/ | title=Brothers hoping to join the county set | date=19 August 2007 | first=Bill | last=Marshall | newspaper=Bradford Telegraph and Argus | accessdate=13 March 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Early career==\n\n===Early promise===\nRashid showed promise from a young age: Jenner spotted him as a 14-year-old,<ref name=\"Spinning into the spotlight\" /> and, in early July 2005, aged 17, he took 6\u201313 for Yorkshire's Academy (youth) team.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://cricketarchive.co.uk/Archive/Scorecards/82/82850.html | title=Sheffield United v Yorkshire Academy in 2005 | accessdate=12 May 2007 | publisher=CricketArchive}}</ref> A few days later he hit 111 for Yorkshire Cricket Board Under-17s against their Cheshire equivalents in the Under-17s County Championship.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://cricketarchive.co.uk/Archive/Scorecards/82/82889.html | title=Yorkshire Cricket Board Under-17s v Cheshire Cricket Board Under-17s in 2005 | accessdate=12 May 2007 | publisher=CricketArchive}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, he played a number of games for Yorkshire Second XI, making four successive [[century (cricket)|centuries]].<ref name=\"Spinning into the spotlight\" />\nThis form, combined with a calf injury to [[Darren Lehmann]],\nearned him the chance to make his [[first-class cricket|first-class]] debut.\n\n===2006: County debut and youth Tests===\nRashid made his county cricket debut against [[Warwickshire County Cricket Club|Warwickshire]] at [[North Marine Road]], [[Scarborough, North Yorkshire|Scarborough]], as a replacement for injured overseas batsman [[Darren Lehmann]]. In the second innings he bowled a magnificent 6/67 to rip through Warwickshire's middle order and win the match for Yorkshire.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://cricketarchive.co.uk/Archive/Scorecards/85/85803.html | title= Yorkshire v Warwickshire in 2006 | accessdate=12 May 2007 | publisher=CricketArchive}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket/content/story/254122.html|title=Debutant Rashid spins Yorkshire fine victory {{!}} Cricket|date=21 July 2006|access-date=13 October 2008|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8052/scorecard/225042/yorkshire-vs-birmingham-bears-county-championship-division-one-2006|title=County Championship Division One at Scarborough, Jul 19-21 2006 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> Rashid was then included in the [[England Under-19 cricket team|England Under-19s]] Test squad for their series against [[India Under-19 cricket team|India Under-19s]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/251578.html|title=Chopra handed Under-19 captaincy {{!}} Cricket|date=27 June 2006|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> Making his debut for the side in the first Test at [[St Lawrence Ground|Canterbury]], he scored 13 and 23 runs and took one wicket.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/engine/match/239927.html | title=England Under-19s v India Under-19s at Canterbury, Jul 26\u201329, 2006| accessdate=12 May 2007 | publisher=[[Cricinfo]]}}</ref><!--The opening line of his ECB profile says he was called up for the *second* Test; this is clearly wrong, as Rashid's appearance on the first Test scoreboard proves, and indeed the correct \"first Test\" is used lower down the same ECB article!--> In the second Test, at [[County Ground, Taunton|Taunton]], he produced a dominant all-round display, scoring 114 and 48 and claiming 8/157 and 2/45.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/engine/match/239928.html | title=England Under-19s v India Under-19s at Taunton, Aug 1\u20134, 2006 | accessdate=12 May 2007 | publisher=[[Cricinfo]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/255457.html|title=Rashid leads England fightback {{!}} Cricket|date=2 August 2006|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/255527.html|title=Rashid's allround heroics give England the edge {{!}} Cricket|date=3 August 2006|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/255620.html|title=Rashid and Chopra star again in stalemate {{!}} Cricket|date=4 August 2006|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/14595/scorecard/239928/england-under-19s-vs-india-under-19s-2nd-youth-test-india-under-19s-tour-of-england-2006|title=2nd Youth Test, India Under-19s tour of England at Taunton, Aug 1-4 2006 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> He also played in the third Test at the Denis Compton Oval in [[Shenley, Hertfordshire|Shenley]], but made less of an impression, only taking three wickets and scoring 15 and 12 runs.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/engine/match/239929.html | title=England Under-19s v India Under-19s at Shenley, Aug 6\u20139, 2006 | accessdate=12 May 2007 | publisher=[[Cricinfo]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/14595/scorecard/239929/england-under-19s-vs-india-under-19s-3rd-youth-test-india-under-19s-tour-of-england-2006|title=3rd Youth Test, India Under-19s tour of England at Shenley, Aug 6-9 2006 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nFrom mid-August until the end of the season, he held down a regular spot in the Yorkshire side.<ref name=\"Player Oracle\">{{cite web | url=http://cricketarchive.co.uk/cgi-bin/ask_the_player_oracle.cgi?playernumber=88341 | title=Player Oracle | accessdate=12 May 2007 | publisher=CricketArchive}}</ref> He continued to impress, taking 4/96 against [[Middlesex County Cricket Club|Middlesex]] at Scarborough<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket/content/story/258360.html|title=Goodwin blasts century for Sussex {{!}} Cricket|date=1 September 2006|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8052/scorecard/225060/yorkshire-vs-middlesex-county-championship-division-one-2006|title=County Championship Division One at Scarborough, Aug 30 - Sep 2 2006 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> and scoring 63, his maiden first-class half-century, against [[Nottinghamshire County Cricket Club|Nottinghamshire]] at [[Headingley Stadium|Headingley]] as part of a fourth-wicket stand of 130 with [[Craig White]] to dig Yorkshire out of a hole from 42/3 before helping to bowl out Nottinghamshire's tail to win the match for Yorkshire.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://cricketarchive.co.uk/Archive/Scorecards/86/86060.html | title=Yorkshire v Nottinghamshire in 2006 | accessdate=12 May 2007 | publisher=CricketArchive}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket/content/story/259514.html|title=Lancashire frustrated by plodding Durham {{!}} Cricket|date=13 September 2006|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket/content/story/259758.html|title=Cork special boost Lancashire {{!}} Cricket|date=16 September 2006|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8052/scorecard/225067/yorkshire-vs-nottinghamshire-county-championship-division-one-2006|title=County Championship Division One at Leeds, Sep 13-16 2006 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> Rashid also featured in a two-day \"spin match\" held by the [[England and Wales Cricket Board]], a programme which would simulate different match-based scenarios to develop young spin bowlers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/258416.html|title=Youngsters set for 'spin match' {{!}} Cricket|date=2 September 2006|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\n===2007: Young Player of the Year===\nDuring the winter, Rashid suffered from a [[stress fracture]] in his back<ref name=\"ECB profile\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket/content/story/273887.html|title=Rashid on the mend {{!}} Cricket|date=25 December 2006|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> and missed England Under-19s' tour of Malaysia, but he recovered well enough to be picked for the 2006\u201307 [[England A cricket team|England A]] tour of Bangladesh.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/274842.html|title=Yardy handed England A captaincy {{!}} Cricket|date=2 January 2007|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> Despite unimpressive performances, he was tipped by Yorkshire teammate [[Jason Gillespie]] to play international cricket for England in the future.<ref name=gillespie>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/284948.html|title=Gillespie tips Rashid for international stardom {{!}} Cricket|date=12 March 2007|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote|text=Adil is probably the best young cricketer in England ... I think he could play an allround role for England in the future.|author=[[Jason Gillespie]]<ref name=gillespie/>}}\n\nRashid started the English summer at [[Lord's]], playing for [[Marylebone Cricket Club]] (MCC) against the 2006 champion county, [[Sussex County Cricket Club|Sussex]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://cricketarchive.co.uk/Archive/Scorecards/107/107653.html | title=Marylebone Cricket Club v Sussex in 2007 | accessdate=12 May 2007 | publisher=CricketArchive}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/288679.html|title=Harmison and Hoggard lead MCC attack {{!}} Cricket|date=5 April 2007|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> In his [[County Championship]] game of the season, at [[The Oval]] against [[Surrey County Cricket Club|Surrey]] a few days later, he hit 86 in the first innings, putting on 190 with [[Jacques Rudolph]] for the sixth wicket.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://cricketarchive.co.uk/Archive/Scorecards/107/107662.html | title=Surrey v Yorkshire in 2007 | accessdate=12 May 2007 | publisher=CricketArchive}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2007/content/story/291279.html|title=Sussex start defence in style {{!}} Cricket|date=18 April 2007|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8052/scorecard/268048/surrey-vs-yorkshire-county-championship-division-one-2007|title=County Championship Division One at London, Apr 18-21 2007 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> This established a new partnership record for the sixth wicket for Yorkshire against Surrey, surpassing a mark that had stood since 1902.<ref>{{cite news|first=David|last=Warner|title=Bowler leads glut of batting records in breathtaking start for Yorkshire regime|url=http://www.yorkshireccc.com/reportscards/lvchampionship2007/asurryork|publisher=[[Yorkshire County Cricket Club]]|accessdate=12 May 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070515042559/http://www.yorkshireccc.com/reportscards/lvchampionship2007/asurryork|archivedate=15 May 2007|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> At the end of April he continued to impress with bowling figures of 5/88 against [[Durham County Cricket Club|Durham]] at Headingley.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://cricketarchive.co.uk/Archive/Scorecards/107/107675.html | title=Yorkshire v Durham in 2007 | accessdate=12 May 2007 | publisher=CricketArchive}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2007/content/story/292328.html|title=Rashid continues to impress|date=25 April 2007|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8052/scorecard/268054/yorkshire-vs-durham-county-championship-division-one-2007|title=County Championship Division One at Leeds, Apr 25-27 2007 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> Due to his form he was picked to play for [[England Lions (cricket team)|England Lions]] in a tour match against [[India national cricket team|India]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/14366/scorecard/275786/england-lions-vs-india-tour-match-india-tour-of-ireland-england-and-scotland-2007|title=Tour Match, India tour of Ireland, England and Scotland at Chelmsford, Jul 13-15 2007 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nRashid was considered to play for England's Under-19 side again in their series against [[Pakistan Under-19 cricket team|Pakistan]], but his Yorkshire coach [[Martyn Moxon]] showed displeasure at the idea of Rashid being pulled away from county cricket. The selectors decided that as Rashid had progressed to the next level of cricket, having appeared for England Lions, and therefore he shouldn't be pulled out of county cricket to play for England Under-19s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/303055.html|title=Rashid withdrawn from Under-19 series {{!}} Cricket|date=21 July 2007|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/303622.html|title=Hamilton-Brown defends Under-19 cricket {{!}} Cricket|last=Thompson|first=Jenny|date=25 July 2007|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> In continuing to play county cricket, he scored his maiden first-class century, 108 against [[Worcestershire County Cricket Club|Worcestershire]] at Kidderminster,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/303622.html|title=Batty guides Surrey to the draw {{!}} Cricket|date=16 August 2007|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2007/content/story/307215.html|title=Declaration and Ali burst bring game to life {{!}} Cricket|last=Ward|first=John|date=16 August 2007|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2007/content/story/307289.html|title=Smith guides Worcestershire run chase {{!}} Cricket|last=Ward|first=John|date=17 August 2007|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8052/scorecard/268101/worcestershire-vs-yorkshire-county-championship-division-one-2007|title=County Championship Division One at Kidderminster, Aug 14-17 2007 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> and another half-century against [[Warwickshire County Cricket Club|Warwickshire]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2007/content/story/308056.html|title=Rudolph double flays Warwickshire {{!}} Cricket|last=Ward|first=John|date=23 August 2007|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8052/scorecard/268105/yorkshire-vs-birmingham-bears-county-championship-division-one-2007|title=County Championship Division One at Scarborough, Aug 22-24 2007 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nOver the course of the 2007 English cricket season, Rashid scored 837 with a batting average of 44.05 and took 43 wickets with a bowling average of 42.16 across all first-class matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/88/88341/f_Batting_by_Season.html|title=First-class Batting and Fielding in Each Season by Adil Rashid|access-date=13 October 2018|work=CricketArchive|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/88/88341/f_Bowling_by_Season.html|title=First-class Bowling in Each Season by Adil Rashid|access-date=13 October 2018|work=CricketArchive}}</ref> He took the most wickets of any Yorkshire player and scored the fourth-most runs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/averages/batting_bowling_by_team.html?id=2991;team=1515;type=tournament|title=Cricket Records {{!}} Records {{!}} County Championship Division One, 2007 - Yorkshire {{!}} {{!}} Batting and bowling averages|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> He won several awards in 2007 for his strong form. In June 2007 he won both the YCCSA Young Player of the Year Award for 2006<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yorkshireccc.com/news/copy_of_news716202446 |title=Latest Cricket News &#124; YCCC News |publisher=Yorkshireccc.com |accessdate=24 February 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928000526/http://www.yorkshireccc.com/news/copy_of_news716202446 |archivedate=28 September 2007 }}</ref> and the Neil Lloyd Young Cricketer of the Year Award for 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yorkshireccc.com/news/news716202446 |title=Latest Cricket News &#124; YCCC News |publisher=Yorkshireccc.com |accessdate=24 February 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928000625/http://www.yorkshireccc.com/news/news716202446 |archivedate=28 September 2007 }}</ref> On 9 September Rashid was named 2007 [[Cricket Writers' Club Young Cricketer of the Year]], while on 24 September he was awarded the title of [[PCA Young Player of the Year]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ecb.co.uk/domestic/gibson-reaps-top-award,15154,EN.html |title=Gibson lands top award |accessdate=25 September 2007 |publisher=[[England and Wales Cricket Board|ECB]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071118093405/http://ecb.co.uk/domestic/gibson-reaps-top-award%2C15154%2CEN.html |archivedate=18 November 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/312374.html|title=Gibson picks up PCA's Most Valuable Player award {{!}} Cricket|date=24 September 2007|access-date=13 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2007, Rashid was named in the \"England Performance Programme squad\", to train at home and in India during the 2007\u201308 winter.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/7030274.stm | work=BBC News | title=Broad named in development squad | date=5 October 2007 | accessdate=23 April 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/313831.html|title=England name strong performance squad {{!}} Cricket|date=5 October 2007|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\n===2008: First tour with national team===\n{{See also|English cricket team in the West Indies in 2008\u201309}}\nIn January 2008, Rashid was named in the England Lions squad for the [[2007\u201308 Duleep Trophy]] in India.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/328905.html|title=Prior dropped as Ambrose gets his chance {{!}} Cricket|date=4 January 2008|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> He played two games for the tournament and took six wickets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/averages/batting_bowling_by_team.html?id=3434;team=1003;type=tournament|title=Cricket Records {{!}} Records {{!}} Duleep Trophy, 2007/08 - England Lions {{!}} {{!}} Batting and bowling averages|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> For the second season in a row he was also named in the Marylebone Cricket Club squad to play against the champion county, this time [[Sussex County Cricket Club|Sussex]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2008/content/story/344588.html|title=Sussex to face strong MCC outfit {{!}} Cricket|date=31 March 2008|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/345730.html|title=Sussex primed for season curtain-raise {{!}} Cricket|date=9 April 2008|access-date=14 October 2008|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> He also retained his place in the England Performance Programme squad.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/7358539.stm | work=BBC News | title=England selectors look at Rashid | date=21 April 2008 | accessdate=23 April 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/story/347210.html|title=Key given hope of England recall {{!}} Cricket|date=21 April 2008|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nThere was concern early in the season that Rashid's bowling was losing some of its variety as it seemed his batting was taking precedence,<ref name=topoftheclass>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/magazine/content/story/371053.html |title=Top of the class |publisher=Cricinfo.com |author=Andrew McGlashan |date=25 September 2008 |postscript=<!--None-->}} Retrieved on 4 December 2008.</ref> but he then took career-best bowling figures of 7/107 against [[Hampshire County Cricket Club|Hampshire]] at the [[Rose Bowl, Hampshire|Rose Bowl]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2008/content/story/364023.html|title=Durham sense victory after 23 wickets fall {{!}} Cricket|date=7 August 2008|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8052/scorecard/319925/hampshire-vs-yorkshire-county-championship-division-one-2008|title=County Championship Division One at Southampton, Aug 6-8 2008 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> He followed this up with hauls of 5/95 against [[Lancashire County Cricket Club|Lancashire]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2008/content/story/364804.html|title=Croft holds up Yorkshire's progress {{!}} Cricket|last=Ward|first=John|date=13 August 2008|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2008/content/story/365018.html|title=Gale and McGrath grind down Lancashire {{!}} Cricket|last=Ward|first=John|date=14 August 2008|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8052/scorecard/319927/lancashire-vs-yorkshire-county-championship-division-one-2008|title=County Championship Division One at Manchester, Aug 12-15 2008 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> and 7/136 against [[Sussex County Cricket Club|Sussex]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2008/content/story/371420.html|title=Goodwin and Rashid bask in the sun {{!}} Cricket|last=Williamson|first=Martin|date=27 September 2008|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8052/scorecard/319950/sussex-vs-yorkshire-county-championship-division-one-2008|title=County Championship Division One at Brighton, Sep 24-27 2008 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> Rashid finished the season with 62 wickets, Yorkshire's leading wicket-taker for the second year in a row.<ref name=topoftheclass/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/averages/batting_bowling_by_team.html?id=3632;team=1515;type=tournament|title=Cricket Records {{!}} Records {{!}} County Championship Division One, 2008 - Yorkshire {{!}} {{!}} Batting and bowling averages|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of the year, Rashid was included in the [[England national cricket team|English national team]] for their [[English cricket team in India in 2008\u201309|tour of India]], though he wasn't expected to be any chance of playing a match for England, only being on the tour for the experience.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/indveng/content/story/381098.html|title=Amjad Khan earns call-up {{!}} Cricket|date=7 December 2008|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/7769870.stm | work=BBC News | title=England call up Khan and Rashid | date=7 December 2008 | accessdate=23 April 2010}}</ref> He was then included in England's squad for their following [[English cricket team in the West Indies in 2008\u201309|tour of the West Indies]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wiveng2009/content/story/386961.html|title=Rashid ready to take his chance {{!}} Cricket|date=19 January 2009|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> where he was part of England's team for a tour match against a [[Saint Kitts and Nevis]] team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wiveng2009/content/story/387701.html|title=Chance for Shah as England play 11 {{!}} Cricket|date=24 January 2009|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/13775/scorecard/352670/st-kitts-invitational-xi-vs-england-tour-match-england-tour-of-west-indies-2008-09|title=Tour Match, England tour of West Indies at Basseterre, Jan 25-27 2009 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> National selector [[Geoff Miller]], described Rashid's selection at the age of 20 in the following terms:\n\n{{Quote|text=Adil Rashid... is an exciting prospect for the future and his inclusion will enable us to continue to monitor his development closely as well as providing extra competition for places in the spin-bowling department.|author=[[Geoff Miller]]<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/7802062.stm | work=BBC News | title=Vaughan misses out on tour place | date=29 December 2008 | accessdate=23 April 2010}}</ref>}}\n\n==Early international call-ups==\n===2009: World Twenty20 and ODI debut===\n{{See also|2009 ICC World Twenty20|English cricket team in Ireland in 2009|Australian cricket team in England and Scotland in 2009}}\nRashid was again included in the England Lions team for a tour match against the West Indies,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/engvwi2009/content/story/400935.html|title=Bell gets Lions call and Key leads {{!}} Cricket|date=22 April 2009|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> and he had a good all-round performance, scoring 72 runs in England Lions' first innings and taking 3/66 in the West Indies' second innings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/engvwi2009/content/story/402637.html|title=England Lions hammer West Indies {{!}} Cricket|date=2 May 2009|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/13683/scorecard/383273/england-lions-vs-west-indies-tour-match-west-indies-tour-of-england-2009|title=Tour Match, West Indies tour of England at Derby, Apr 30 - May 2 2009 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> Despite not being included in Yorkshire's side for their first two [[Twenty20]] matches of the season, Rashid's form saw him called up to the national team for the [[2009 ICC World Twenty20]] as an injury replacement for [[Andrew Flintoff]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wt202009/content/story/406257.html|title=Flintoff ruled out of World Twenty20 {{!}} Cricket|last=Miller|first=Andrew|date=27 May 2009|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> In England's first warm-up match for the tournament against [[Scotland national cricket team|Scotland]], Rashid appeared nervous, but in their second warm-up match against the West Indies he appeared more settled and took 1/20 from his 4 overs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wt202009/content/story/407237.html|title=Wright and Bopara crush West Indies {{!}} Cricket|last=McGlashan|first=Andrew|date=3 June 2009|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wt202009/content/story/407237.html|title=(D/N)ICC World Twenty20 Warm-up Matches at London, Jun 3 2009 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> During the tournament itself he had impressive performances against [[Pakistan national cricket team|Pakistan]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wt202009/content/story/407237.html|title=By jove, it's a six from England {{!}} Cricket|last=Miller|first=Andrew|date=3 June 2007|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8604/scorecard/355996/england-vs-pakistan-6th-match-group-b-icc-world-twenty20-2009|title=6th Match, Group B (D/N), ICC World Twenty20 at London, Jun 7 2009 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> and the West Indies,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wt202009/content/story/409158.html|title=Mettle, experience, comebacks and bravery {{!}} Cricket|last=Miller|first=Andrew|date=15 June 2009|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8604/scorecard/356011/england-vs-west-indies-22nd-match-group-e-icc-world-twenty20-2009|title=22nd Match, Group E (D/N), ICC World Twenty20 at London, Jun 15 2009 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> and he finished the tournament with 3 wickets at an average of 31.66 and with an economy of 7.30 runs per over from his 4 matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/wt202009/engine/records/averages/batting_bowling_by_team.html?id=4162;team=1;type=tournament|title=Cricket Records {{!}} Records {{!}} ICC World Twenty20, 2009 - England {{!}} {{!}} Batting and bowling averages|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his World Twenty20 appearances, he was included in England's training squad for the [[2009 Ashes series]] against [[Australia national cricket team|Australia]], thought to be a potential replacement for the out-of-form [[Monty Panesar]], but instead of playing a warm-up game with the England XI he played with England Lions again in a tour match against Australia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/engvaus2009/content/story/410113.html|title=Vaughan and Harmison wait on training squad {{!}} Cricket|last=McGlashan|first=Andrew|date=21 June 2009|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/engvaus2009/content/story/410177.html|title=Vaughan and Harmison left out of Ashes squad {{!}} Cricket|date=22 June 2009|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/13659/scorecard/350039/england-lions-vs-australia-tour-match-australia-tour-of-england-and-scotland-2009|title=Tour Match, Australia tour of England and Scotland at Worcester, Jul 1-4 2009 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> He was left out of England's final squad for the Ashes<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/engvaus2009/content/story/412829.html|title=Onions pips Harmison for final slot {{!}} Cricket|last=Miller|first=Andrew|date=5 July 2009|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> and instead returned to playing county cricket with Yorkshire. Rashid scored his career-best 117 [[not out]] and later on helped Yorkshire to bowl [[Hampshire County Cricket Club|Hampshire]] out with figures of 5/41.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2009/content/story/419387.html|title=Nash powers Sussex to win {{!}} Cricket|date=13 August 2009|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2009/content/story/419713.html|title=Rashid five routs Hampshire {{!}} Cricket|date=14 August 2009|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8052/scorecard/382957/hampshire-vs-yorkshire-county-championship-division-one-2009|title=County Championship Division One at Basingstoke, Aug 11-14 2009 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> He then went on to better that against [[Lancashire County Cricket Club|Lancashire]], scoring an unbeaten 157 and taking 5/97 in the first innings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2009/content/story/420952.html|title=Rashid and Bopara in the runs {{!}} Cricket|date=21 August 2009|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8052/scorecard/382963/yorkshire-vs-lancashire-county-championship-division-one-2009|title=County Championship Division One at Leeds, Aug 19-22 2009 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> The feat of scoring a century and taking a five-for in a match was the third of his career; the last player to have achieved the feat twice in a season for Yorkshire was [[George Hirst]] back in 1911.<ref>{{cite web|author=Andy Wilson |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2009/aug/21/adil-rashid-yorkshire-lancashire-county-championship |title=Adil Rashid underlines potential with 136 for Yorkshire in Roses match &#124; Sport |work=The Guardian|date=21 August 2009 |accessdate=24 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nRashid made his [[One Day International]] debut for England on 27 August 2009 against [[Ireland national cricket team|Ireland]]. He scored 7 runs and had bowling figures of 1/16 in a narrow win.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/13527/scorecard/383275/ireland-vs-england-only-odi-england-tour-of-ireland-2009|title=Only ODI, England tour of Ireland at Belfast, Aug 27 2009 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> He kept his place in the side for the 1st ODI against Australia, and he was the best of England's bowlers, only conceding 37 runs from his 10 overs. He followed this up with a quickfire 31 not out from just 23 balls with the bat to almost get England across the line in a tight finish.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/engvaus2009/content/story/423493.html|title=Rashid shines but Australia hold nerve {{!}} Cricket|last=Miller|first=Andrew|date=4 September 2009|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/13659/scorecard/350043/england-vs-australia-1st-odi-australia-tour-of-england-and-scotland-2009|title=1st ODI (D/N), Australia tour of England and Scotland at London, Sep 4 2009 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> He impressed Australians [[Michael Clarke (cricketer)|Michael Clarke]] and [[James Hopes]] with his strong performance,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/engvaus2009/content/story/423605.html|title=Rashid maturity impresses Aussies {{!}} Cricket|last=Miller|first=Andrew|date=4 September 2009|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/engvaus2009/content/story/423662.html|title=Rashid's Australian connection {{!}} Cricket|last=McGlashan|first=Andrew|date=5 September 2009|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> but he was shockingly omitted from the English side for the next match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/engvaus2009/content/story/423759.html|title=England's batsmen not learning {{!}} Cricket|last=McGlashan|first=Andrew|date=6 September 2009|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> He did return for two more matches during the series, but finished with only 2 wickets at an average of 74.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/averages/batting_bowling_by_team.html?id=4287;team=1;type=series|title=Cricket Records {{!}} Records {{!}} NatWest Series [Australia in England], 2009 - England {{!}} {{!}} Batting and bowling averages|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\n===2009\u201310: South Africa and Pakistan A===\n{{See also|English cricket team in South Africa in 2009\u201310}}\nRashid completely supplanted Monty Panesar in the England side, being named as the back-up to [[Graeme Swann]] for both the Test and ODI squads in their [[English cricket team in South Africa in 2009\u201310|tour of South Africa]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/rsaveng09/content/story/428799.html|title=Harmison and Bopara miss out for South Africa tour {{!}} Cricket|date=8 October 2009|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> He played in the second Twenty20 International between the sides, but was only used for one over in which he conceded 25 runs, after which South Africa's coach [[Mickey Arthur]] criticized the English side for not showing enough faith in Rashid's ability.<ref name=EPP>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/rsaveng09/content/story/437654.html|title=Davids stars but Test candidates struggle against Gauteng|date=30 November 2009|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/13436/scorecard/387564/south-africa-vs-england-2nd-t20i-england-tour-of-south-africa-2009-10|title=2nd T20I, England tour of South Africa at Centurion, Nov 15 2009 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> Due to an injury to Swann, Rashid was brought back into the side for the 2nd ODI, but he bowled an expensive three overs, conceding 27 runs, and was dropped once Swann was fit again.<ref name=eastlondonwarmup>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/rsaveng09/content/story/438621.html|title=Anderson ruled out of England warm-up {{!}} Cricket|last=McGlashan|first=Andrew|date=8 December 2009|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/13436/scorecard/387566/south-africa-vs-england-2nd-odi-england-tour-of-south-africa-2009-10|title=2nd ODI, England tour of South Africa at Centurion, Nov 22 2009 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> He was then dropped from South Africa's ODI squad altogether for the rest of the series, instead playing four-day matches with the England Performance Programme. Meanwhile, offspinner [[James Tredwell]] remained on stand-by to potentially play, indicating that Rashid had dropped down the pecking order.<ref name=EPP/><ref name=eastlondonwarmup/> His poor form continued in the England Performance Programme matches,<ref name=EPP/> and though he re-joined the main squad ahead of the Test series he did not play in any Test matches.<ref name=eastlondonwarmup/>\n\nFollowing the poor tour for Rashid, he was left out of England's squad for their [[English cricket team in Bangladesh in 2009\u201310|tour of Bangladesh]], instead being sent to the [[United Arab Emirates]] to play for England Lions against [[Pakistan A cricket team|Pakistan A]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/445084.html|title=Time out will help Adil Rashid - Andy Flower {{!}} Cricket|date=19 January 2010|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> His time in the UAE was somewhat more successful than his time in South Africa, and he took 3/13 in the second Twenty20 against Pakistan A to secure a series win for England Lions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/448230.html|title=England Lions secure series with second win {{!}} Cricket|date=14 February 2010|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/13354/scorecard/443089/england-lions-vs-pakistan-a-2nd-match-pakistan-a-tour-of-united-arab-emirates-2009-10|title=2nd Match, Pakistan A tour of United Arab Emirates at Sharjah, Feb 14 2010 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> After the Twenty20 series against Pakistan A, England Lions also played a Twenty20 against the main England team and Rashid helped cause a shock upset win with another strong bowling performance of 3/22.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/pakveng2010/content/story/448772.html|title=Kieswetter and Lumb leads Lions victory {{!}} Cricket|date=17 February 2010|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/13344/scorecard/443095/england-vs-england-lions-tour-match-england-lions-tour-of-united-arab-emirates-2009-10|title=Tour Match (D/N), England Lions tour of United Arab Emirates at Abu Dhabi, Feb 17 2010 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\n==Continued domestic career==\n[[File:Adil Rashid sharp.jpg|thumb|right|150px|Rashid playing for Yorkshire in 2010]]\n\n===2010\u201311: Overlooked by national selectors; Big Bash===\nFollowing his unsuccessful winter abroad, Rashid returned to playing county cricket with Yorkshire in the 2010 summer. He immediately showed that he still had the potential to return to the English national team, showing his batting skills with an impressive innings against Warwickshire in his first match of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2010/content/story/455513.html|title=Yorkshire edge lead in fluctuating battle {{!}} Cricket|last=Dobell|first=George|date=10 April 2010|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8052/scorecard/435399/birmingham-bears-vs-yorkshire-county-championship-division-one-2010|title=County Championship Division One at Birmingham, Apr 9-12 2010 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> His self-confidence returned throughout the season and he had several impressive performances with both ball and bat in the county championship,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2010/content/story/460259.html|title=Lyth lights up run-glut at Taunton {{!}} Cricket|date=19 May 2010|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2010/content/story/461013.html|title=Batsmen put Yorkshire in command {{!}} Cricket|date=26 May 2010|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2010/content/story/465529.html|title=McGrath steadies Yorkshire towards a draw {{!}} Cricket|last=Culley|first=Jon|date=30 June 2010|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2010/content/story/466611.html|title=Yorkshire victory builds Championship lead {{!}} Cricket|last=Culley|first=Jon|date=8 July 2010|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2010/content/story/468335.html|title=Adam Lyth impresses but Essex retain edge {{!}} Cricket|date=21 July 2010|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2010/content/story/473981.html|title=Adil Rashid lifts Yorkshire after Dominic Cork burst {{!}} Cricket|date=24 August 2018|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> finishing the season with 732 runs at 45.75 and 57 wickets at 31.29,<ref name=201011ashes>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/the-ashes-2010-11/content/story/478475.html|title=Chris Tremlett and Monty Panesar earn Ashes calls {{!}} Cricket|last=McGlashan|first=Andrew|date=23 September 2010|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> as well as taking 26 wickets in the [[2010 Twenty20 Cup]], the most of the Yorkshire bowlers and the fourth-most overall.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=5610;type=tournament|title=Cricket Records {{!}} Records {{!}} Friends Provident t20, 2010 {{!}} {{!}} Most wickets|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> Despite his strong performances throughout the season he was still overlooked by English selectors, being left out of their home series against [[Bangladesh national cricket team|Bangladesh]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2010/content/story/466363.html|title=Adil Rashid spins Yorkshire ahead {{!}} Cricket|last=Culley|first=Jon|date=6 July 2010|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> and the squad for the [[2010\u201311 Ashes series]] in favour of Monty Panesar.<ref name=201011ashes/>\n\nNot having been selected to play for England over the 2010\u201311 winter, Rashid instead played for [[South Australia cricket team|South Australia]] in the [[2010\u201311 KFC Twenty20 Big Bash]]. He played a useful role in the team alongside fellow spinner [[Nathan Lyon]], and finished the season with 10 wickets, one behind the tournament's leaders Lyon and [[Pat Cummins]], as South Australia won the tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8627/report/461041/tasmania-vs-south-australia-twenty20-big-bash-2010-11|title=(D/N)Twenty20 Big Bash at Hobart, Jan 24 2011 {{!}} Match Report|last=Malcolm|first=Alex|date=23 January 2011|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=5899;type=tournament|title=Cricket Records {{!}} Records {{!}} Twenty20 Big Bash, 2010/11 {{!}} {{!}} Most wickets|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> Following the Big Bash, Rashid was selected to play for England Lions on a tour of the West Indies, during which they played in the local first-class competition, the [[2010\u201311 Regional Four Day Competition]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/492748.html|title=England news: Steven Finn and Ravi Bopara included in Lions squad {{!}} Cricket|date=15 December 2010|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\n===2011\u201312: Decline in form===\nRashid started the 2011 season well by taking 6/77 and 5/37 in Yorkshire's opening match against Worcestershire,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2011/content/story/510016.html|title=Worcestershire v Yorkshire: Rashid bags six on opening day {{!}} Cricket|last=Dobell|first=George|date=8 April 2011|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8052/report/492088/day/3/|title=County Championship Division One at Worcester, Apr 8-10 2011 {{!}} Match Report|last=Dobell|first=george|date=10 April 2011|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8052/scorecard/492088/worcestershire-vs-yorkshire-county-championship-division-one-2011|title=County Championship Division One at Worcester, Apr 8-10 2011 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> but overall he struggled for form, and conceded the worst bowling figures of his career, and the third-worst ever for Yorkshire, when he bowled no wicket for 187 runs against [[Sussex County Cricket Club|Sussex]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2011/content/story/517235.html|title=Sussex v Yorkshire: Murray Goodwin builds huge Sussex total {{!}} Cricket|date=30 May 2011|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8052/scorecard/492116/sussex-vs-yorkshire-county-championship-division-one-2011|title=County Championship Division One at Brighton, May 29 - Jun 1 2011 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> His poor form continued into the 2012 season, and he found himself dropped from Yorkshire's team for the first time in his county career. This came as a result of his worst ever start to a county season, taking nine wickets at 49.00 in his first six matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2012/content/story/566627.html|title=County Cricket 2012: Adil Rashid left out by Yorkshire {{!}} Cricket|last=Winter|first=Alex|date=29 May 2012|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> Yorkshire's president [[Geoffrey Boycott]] lamented that Rashid had not appeared to progress at all since he started playing county cricket, and said that Rashid needed to take responsibility for his poor performances.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2012/content/story/566751.html|title=County Cricket 2012: Adil Rashid the one to blame - Boycott|last=Hodgson|first=Myles|date=30 May 2012|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> In ten first-class matches in 2012 he took just 16 wickets at an average of 41 and made 129 runs at 16.12, his decline meaning he was no longer even asked to play for England Lions anymore.<ref name=yorkshirerift>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2013/content/story/629006.html|title=Yorkshire forced to deny Adil Rashid rift {{!}} Cricket|date=9 April 2013|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\n===2013\u201314: Return to form===\nJust hours before the start of the 2013 county season, Rashid was quoted by ''[[the Independent]]'' as saying that if his 2013 season didn't go well he'd request to go on loan from Yorkshire to a different county, which forced Yorkshire to deny that there was any rift between Rashid and the club. Martyn Moxon, then Yorkshire's director of cricket, said that the interview had been in January, months before the start of the season and that there hadn't been any issues.<ref name=yorkshirerift/> Rashid also showed that his poor form was behind him as he started the season with his highest first-class score, a 180 against [[Somerset County Cricket Club|Somerset]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2013/content/story/634592.html|title=Adil Rashid proves agreeable for Yorkshire {{!}} Cricket|last=Hopps|first=David|date=7 May 2013|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2013/content/story/634745.html|title=Adil Rashid's best continues run-scoring spree {{!}} Cricket|last=Smith|first=Les|date=8 May 2013|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8052/scorecard/593476/yorkshire-vs-somerset-county-championship-division-one-2013|title=County Championship Division One at Leeds, May 7-10 2013 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> He followed this up with two more centuries, one against Warwickshire and a second against Somerset, taking his average for the county season up to that point above 200.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2013/content/story/636498.html|title=Yorkshire breach fortress Edgbaston {{!}} Cricket|last=Hodgson|first=Myles|date=17 May 2013|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2013/content/story/638442.html|title=Marcus Trescothick offers Somerset a glimmer {{!}} Cricket|last=Tennant|first=Ivo|date=30 May 2013|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> In 2014 Rashid continued to improve his bowling, particularly in limited overs cricket, bowling career-best figures of 5/33 in a one-day match against [[Hampshire County Cricket Club|Hampshire]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2014/content/story/773089.html|title=Adil Rashid best earns Yorkshire home tie {{!}} Cricket|date=21 August 2014|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\n==Return to international cricket==\n===2014\u201315: South Africa A, West Indies and Ireland===\n{{See also|English cricket team in the West Indies in 2014\u201315|English cricket team in Ireland in 2015}}\nDue to his form in county cricket, Rashid was named in the England Lions squad for their tour of South Africa in early 2015, set to play in both their first-class and one-day series against [[South Africa A cricket team|South Africa A]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/793775.html|title=Jonathan Trott named in England Lions squad {{!}} Cricket|last=Gardner|first=Alan|date=28 October 2014|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> He batted well on the tour with innings of 78 and 68 in the unofficial Tests.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/11496/scorecard/737427/south-africa-a-vs-england-lions-1st-unofficial-test-england-lions-tour-of-south-africa-2014-15|title=1st unofficial Test, England Lions tour of South Africa at Paarl, jan 11-14 2015 {{!}} Match Summary|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/822007.html|title=Rashid and Lyth keep Lions in the hunt {{!}} Cricket|last=Tennant|first=Ivo|date=18 January 2015|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> In March 2015, Rashid was named in the England Test squad for the [[English cricket team in the West Indies in 2014\u201315|tour of the West Indies]].<ref name=\"ENGSQUAD\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cricket/31942514|title= Jonathan Trott: England recall Warwickshire batsman|publisher=BBC Sport|date=18 March 2015|accessdate=18 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/west-indies-v-england-2015/content/story/852135.html|title=Adam Lyth, Mark Wood and Adil Rashid in Test squad {{!}} Cricket|last=Gardner|first=Alan|date=18 March 2015|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> In the tour matches leading up to England's Test series against the West Indies, Rashid did not perform well enough to get into the Test side, with the selectors favouring James Tredwell ahead of him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/west-indies-v-england-2015/content/story/861563.html|title=Moeen Ali set to replace Adil Rashid {{!}} Cricket|last=Dobell|first=George|date=14 April 2015|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> Despite not being used in the Test matches, he was not allowed to return to England to play with Yorkshire at the beginning of the county cricket season,<ref name=championship>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/871431.html|title=Moeen Ali, Adam Lyth available to play in Championship {{!}} Cricket|date=6 May 2015|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> though Rashid did leave the tour early to join England's ODI team for their [[English cricket team in Ireland in 2015|match against Ireland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/869279.html|title=Adil Rashid, Mark Wood added to squad for Ireland ODI {{!}} Cricket|date=1 May 2015|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> After the match, Yorkshire hired a private jet to fly Rashid back in time for their next county match against [[Hampshire County Cricket Club|Hampshire]], where he took four wickets in each innings.<ref name=championship/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2015/content/story/875155.html|title=Yorkshire wrap up win amid distractions {{!}} Cricket|last=Edwards|first=Paul|date=13 May 2015|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\n===2015: Return to ODI side against New Zealand and Australia===\n{{See also|New Zealand cricket team in England in 2015|Australian cricket team in England and Ireland in 2015}}\nWith the [[2015 Ashes series|2015 Ashes]] around the corner, the English selectors decided to rest Moeen Ali from [[New Zealand cricket team in England in 2015|their ODI series against New Zealand]] and brought in Rashid as his replacement.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england-v-new-zealand-2015/content/story/883659.html|title=James Anderson, Stuart Broad left out of ODI squad {{!}} Cricket|date=2 June 2015|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> Rashid had an immediate impact in the first match of the series, being involved in the [[List of One Day International cricket records#Highest partnership for each wicket|highest 7th wicket partnership of ODI history]] with [[Jos Buttler]], where they scored 177 runs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportskeeda.com/cricket/records-broken-englands-score-4089-first-odi-new-zealand|title=Records broken in England's score of 408/9 in first ODI against New Zealand|author=Dipankar Lahiri|date=9 June 2015}}</ref> Rashid reached his maiden half-century in just 37 balls and went on to score 69 runs, then he gave the most eye-catching bowling of the match as well, making use of his [[googly]] to take the wicket of [[Kane Williamson]] and finishing with figures of 4/55.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england-v-new-zealand-2015/content/story/885449.html|title=Buttler, Root hundreds set up record England win {{!}} Cricket|last=McGlashan|first=Andrew|date=9 June 2015|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> Rashid played all five matches of the series for England and finished with a total of 8 wickets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/averages/batting_bowling_by_team.html?id=9245;team=1;type=series|title=Cricket Records {{!}} Records {{!}} New Zealand in England ODI Series, 2015 - England {{!}} {{!}} Batting and bowling averages|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nRashid was included in England's 13-man squad for the first Test of the Ashes,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/the-ashes-2015/content/story/892951.html|title=Adil Rashid, Steven Finn in England Test squad {{!}} Cricket|date=1 July 2015|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> but the selectors decided that they would only use Rashid in the Test as a second spinner alongside Moeen Ali if there was a spinning pitch.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/the-ashes-2015/content/story/894429.html|title=Spinning pitch at Cardiff 'very unlikely' {{!}} Cricket|date=5 July 2015|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> Rashid remained in the Test squad for every match of the Ashes but did not play,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/the-ashes-2015/content/story/908067.html|title=James Anderson returns to squad for fifth Test {{!}} Cricket|last=McGlashan|first=Andrew|date=9 August 2015|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> and instead he continued playing county cricket for Yorkshire, scoring a century against [[Durham County Cricket Club|Durham]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2015/content/story/907961.html|title=Glenn Maxwell and Adil Rashid reassert Yorkshire dominance {{!}} Cricket|last=Edwards|first=Paul|date=8 August 2015|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> Although he had not played in the Ashes at all, Rashid did get to play in the ODI series against Australia and solidified his spot in the team with figures of 4/59 in the 1st ODI<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/the-ashes-2015/content/story/917129.html|title=Matthew Wade, bowlers put Australia 1-0 up {{!}} Cricket|last=Dobell|first=George|date=3 September 2015|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> and 2/41 in the 3rd ODI.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/the-ashes-2015/content/story/919365.html|title=Adil Rashid gives England gift of legspin {{!}} Cricket|last=McGlashan|first=Andrew|date=10 September 2015|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> Across the five-match series he took 7 wickets, the most of England's bowlers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/the-ashes-2015/engine/records/averages/batting_bowling_by_team.html?id=9255;team=1;type=series|title=Cricket Records {{!}} Records {{!}} Australia in England ODI Series, 2015 - England {{!}} {{!}} Batting and bowling averages|access-date=14 October 2018|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\n===2015 Pakistan===\nIn October 2015, Rashid was selected in the England touring party to play [[Pakistan]] in the [[UAE]] making his debut in the First Test at [[Sheikh Zayed Cricket Stadium]]. Rashid had a torrid time in the first innings of his first match in the Test side, finishing with figures of 0-163 as Pakistan posted 523 - the worst figures by a Test debutant.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/cricket/article-3272386/Adil-Rashid-records-worst-bowling-figures-Test-debutant-0-163-England-against-Pakistan-Abu-Dhabi.html|title=Adil Rashid records worst bowling figures by Test debutant with 0-163|work=Mail Online|access-date=2018-08-13}}</ref> However, he enjoyed a remarkable turn around of fortunes in the next innings, finishing with figures of 5-64, a return that was nearly good enough for England to win the match, although it eventually finished in a draw.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/pakistan-v-england-2015-16/content/story/930075.html|title='Rashid had the character to bounce back' - Moxon|work=Cricinfo|access-date=2018-08-13|language=en}}</ref> In the second Test he took 1-84 in Pakistan's first innings and 1\u2013107 in their second as England lost the game by 178 runs, although Rashid made his maiden Test half-century in England's second innings, hitting 61.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/34635455|title=Pakistan v England: Tourists lose despite Adil Rashid rearguard|date=26 October 2015|work=BBC Sport|access-date=2018-08-13|language=en-GB}}</ref> In the third and final Test, Rashid did not take a wicket in Pakistan's first innings, and in the second innings he finished with 1-97 as England lost the match and the series 2\u20130.\n\nFollowing the Test series, Rashid played in the ODI series. He only took one wicket in the first three games, finishing with figures of 0-60 in the first game, which England lost. After taking 1-32 in the second match, he again finished wicketless in the third match of the series.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/scorecard/ECKP90174|title=Pakistan v England - Cricket|website=BBC Sport|language=en|access-date=2018-08-13}}</ref> He was expensive in the final match of the series, although he did pick up three wickets and England won the match and the series 3\u20131.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/transfer/news/12933/10064101/pakistan-v-england-batting-not-good-enough-from-tourists-says-bumble|title=Pakistan v England: Batting not good enough from tourists, says Bumble|work=SkySports|access-date=2018-08-13|language=en}}</ref>\n\nHe played in all three of the T20 matches. After not bowling or batting in the first game, he took figures of 2-18 in the second game as England secured a three run victory. He took 1-29 in the final game which went to a Super Over, with England winning the matches after the scores finished level.\n\n===2015/16 South Africa===\nAt the urging of coach [[Jason Gillespie]], Rashid signed a deal to play for [[Adelaide Strikers]] in the [[Big Bash in 2015-16]] after being left out of the England squad for the [[English cricket team in South Africa in 2015\u201316|tour of South Africa]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Steve Carroll|url=http://www.yorkpress.co.uk/sport/14094713.Adil_Rashid___quot_I_just_couldn_t_say_no_quot__to_Jason_Gillespie_and_the_Big_Bash/ |title=Adil Rashid: \"I just couldn't say no\" to Jason Gillespie and the Big Bash |publisher=[[York Press]]|date=21 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nRashid was not selected for the Test series against South Africa, although he did keep his place in the ODI side. After failing to take a wicket in the first game, he finished with figures of 1-43 in the second game which England won by five wickets. After taking 1-45 in the third game, he had his bets return of the series in the fourth match. After making 39 with the bat, he took figures of 2-38, although South Africa secured a one wicket victory. In the final match of the series he took figures of 1-59 as South Africa won the match by five wickets to win the series 3\u20132. England lost both T20 matches, although Rashid performed reasonably well, taking figures of 1-24 in the first game and 1-30 in the second game, although England lost by nine wickets.\n\n===2016 T20 World Cup===\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=October 2018}}\nRashid took figures of 1-20 in the opening game against the West Indies, although it wasn't enough to prevent a defeat. In the second game he picked up figures of 1-35 against South Africa, before taking his best figures of the tournament, 2-18 against Afghanistan. With England needing to beat Sri Lanka to qualify for the semi-finals, Rashid finished with figures of 0-31 as England won by ten runs. He did not pick up a wicket against New Zealand in the semi-final, but turned in a good performance in the final against West Indies, taking figures of 1-23. Despite his good performance, England suffered a narrow loss and finished as runners-up.\n\n===2016 Sri Lanka and Pakistan===\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=October 2018}}\nRashid did not pick up a wicket in the first ODI, although he did bowl economically as the match ended in a tie. He took 2-34 in the second match of the series, which England won by ten wickets. In the rain affected third match, he failed to pick up a wicket, and the match was eventually abandoned. In the fourth ODI he took 2-47 as England won by six wickets. He picked up another two wickets in the final game of the series as England completed a 3-0 series win after winning the match by 122 runs. Rashid played in the only T20I between the two sides, and bowled economically, conceding just 25 runs from his four overs, as England won by eight wickets.\n\nRashid took figures of 2-51 in the first ODI against Pakistan, as England got off to a winning start. In the second ODI, he took figures of 1-51 as England restricted Pakistan to 251 and won the match by four wickets. In the third match of the series he took figures of 2-73 as England again won to go 3-0 up in the series. In the fourth match he took figures of 3-47 as England won by four wickets. Rashid was rested for the final match, which England lost. He took figures of 1-29 in the only T20I between the two sides, which England lost by nine wickets.\n\n===2016 Bangladesh===\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=October 2018}}\nIn the first ODI against Bangladesh, Rashid took figures of 4-49 to help England to a 21 run victory. In the second match, he made an unbeaten 33 and took another two wickets, but England lost. In the third match of the series, he took 4-43 as England recorded a four wicket victory to win the series 2\u20131. In the first Test, Rashid scored 26 with the bat before taking 2-58. He took 1-55 in Bangladesh's second innings as England recorded a 22 run victory. In the second Test, Rashid was wicketless in the first innings but took 4-52 in the second innings. England were unable to chase down their target and lost by 108 runs.\n\n===2016-17 India===\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=October 2018}}\nIn the first Test against India, Rashid took figures of 4\u2013114 in India's first innings, before taking 3-64 in their second innings. However, England were unable to force a win and the match ended in a draw. Rashid took 2\u2013110 in India's first innings of the second Test, before making an unbeaten 32 with the bat. He continued to bowl well in India's second innings, taking 4-82, although India won the game by 246 runs. In the third Test he took figures of 4\u2013118 in India's first innings, before taking 1-28 as India secured an eight wicket victory. In the fourth Test, he took figures of 4\u2013192 in India's first innings total of 631, as they won by an innings and 36 runs. In the final match of the series, he made 60 in England's first innings before taking figures of 1-153 as India posted 759/7 and won the match to win the series 4\u20130.\n\nRashid played in the first ODI against India and took figures of 0-50 as England lost by three wickets. He did not feature in the rest of the series, although he retained his place for the T20Is. In the first T20I he did not bat or bowl as England won by seven wickets. In the second match he took 1-24 but England lost by 5 runs as India levelled the series. In the final match of the series he took figures of 0-23 as India made 202/6 and won by 75 runs.\n\nHe was also named as part of the 'Team of the Tournament' at the 2017 Champions Trophy by the ICC,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/champions-trophy/media-releases/421165|title=Live Cricket Scores & News International Cricket Council|website=www.icc-cricket.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref> Cricinfo<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/19678837/captain-sarfraz-pips-kohli-tamim-no-3|title=Champions Trophy XI: Sarfraz pips Kohli, Tamim at No. 3|website=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> and Cricbuzz.\n\n===2017 West Indies and Ireland===\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=October 2018}}\nRashid took 1-43 in the first ODI against the West Indies as England won by 45 runs. In the second match he took 2-53 as England secured a 4 wicket victory. Rashid made nine with bat as England made 328 in the final ODI, before taking 1\u20135 with the ball as England won by 186 runs to win the series 3\u20130. Later in the same year, the West Indies toured England. Rashid's first appearance was in the only T20I, in which he picked up a personal best of 3-25. He continued this good form into the ODI series, taking an economical 2-31 in the first of five, to help restrict the tourists to 204/9. England made light work of the total, as they cruised to a seven wicket victory. Despite the majority of the second ODI being abandoned due to rain, he took 3-34 in the third, while England won by 124 runs. In the final two games, Rashid picked up a solitary wicket in each, although England won both games and celebrated a 4-0 series victory as a consequence.\n\nEngland started their summer by preparing for the [[2017 ICC Champions Trophy|Champions Trophy]], which they were hosting for the second time in succession. Preparation began with two ODIs against [[Ireland cricket team|Ireland]]. In the first ODI, Rashid picked up a career best of 5-27, as Ireland stumbled to 126 all out. England won the game comfortably; they cruised to a seven wicket victory. In the second ODI, Rashid made a speedy 39 from 25 deliveries, although his bowling proved to be less effective, as he took 1-68. England still managed to win the game by 85 runs, and take a 2-0 series victory.\n\n=== 2018 Australia and India ===\n{{main|Indian cricket team in England in 2018}}\nRashid played in all five ODIs against Australia, taking 12 wickets at an average of 21.50.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/averages/batting_bowling_by_team.html?id=12028&team=1&type=series|title=Australia in England ODI Series, 2018 - England Cricket Team Records & Stats {{!}} ESPNcricinfo.com|website=Cricinfo|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2018 Rashid informed Yorkshire of his desire to only play white-ball cricket during the upcoming season, and will not feature in the [[County Championship|county championship]] for the side, preferring to focus on his limited-over career.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://yorkshireccc.com/news/view/6340/rashid-to-focus-on-white-ball-cricket|title=Rashid to focus on white ball cricket|website=Yorkshire County Cricket Club|access-date=2018-02-15}}</ref>\n\nRashid was called up to the England squad to play Test cricket against India in the 2018 series, causing controversy after his decision not to play 4-day county cricket for Yorkshire.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2018/jul/30/adil-rashid-row-alastair-cook-england-india-first-test-edgbaston|title=Adil Rashid will cope with England call-up row, insists Alastair Cook|last=Martin|first=Ali|date=30 July 2018|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-08-13}}</ref> In the second Test, he became the first England cricketer for 13 years to complete a Test match without batting, bowling or taking a catch in the field.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/sports/cricket/india-vs-england-adil-rashid-record-5304496/|title=India vs England: Adil Rashid registers absurd record|date=13 August 2018|work=The Indian Express|access-date=2018-08-13|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n===2019 West Indies and the Cricket World Cup===\nIn [[English cricket team in the West Indies in 2018-19|England's tour of West Indies in 2019]], Rashid was selected in all three squads. He played only one Test, in which his figures were 0\u2013117. In the first ODI he took 3-74, with England winning by 6 wickets. In the second, he took 1-28 in a defeat. In the fourth ODI he took his second ODI five-for, with figures of 5-85 to help England to a 28-run victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/18913/report/1158069/west-indies-vs-england-4th-odi-eng-in-wi-2018-19|title=Recent Match Report: England vs West Indies 4th ODI in Greneda, 27th February 2019|work=EspnCricinfo|accessdate=28 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, he was named in [[2019 Cricket World Cup squads#England|England's squad]] for the [[2019 Cricket World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/story/1181187.html |title=Jofra Archer misses World Cup cut but included to play Ireland, Pakistan |work=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=17 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/1183273 |title=England leave out Jofra Archer from World Cup squad |work=International Cricket Council |accessdate=17 April 2019}}</ref> On 21 June 2019, in the match against [[Sri Lanka national cricket team|Sri Lanka]], Rashid played in his 150th international match for England.<ref name=\"ARJR\">{{cite web|url=https://cricketaddictor.com/cricket/icc-cricket-world-cup-2019-match-27-england-vs-sri-lanka-stats-preview/ |title=ICC Cricket World Cup 2019 (Match 27): England vs Sri Lanka \u2013 Stats Preview |work=Cricket Addictor |accessdate=21 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Bowling style ==\nUnlike [[Shane Warne]], who relies on only one grip on most of his variations (except flipper), and adjust his speed with a slow run-up, Rashid has a quicker run-up, and relies on many grip and arm angle changes on his deliveries, and tends not to be a big turner of the ball, and tends to bowl googlies with three variations alone, which negates his lack of a true flipper, since he bowls them like a normal leg break with quicker wrist action.<ref>{{Citation|title=Leg Spin Masterclass with Shane Warne and Rashid Khan {{!}} The Big Break|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Kk1P_91DaBI|language=en|access-date=2020-01-22}}</ref>\n\n==Charity Work==\nRashid became an Ambassador for the [[Overseas Plastic Surgery Appeal]] charity in November 2018. OPSA are a Yorkshire-based charity that carry out most of their work in the Punjab region of Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web |title=Our Ambassadors \u2013 Overseas Plastic Surgery Appeal (OPSA) |url=https://opsacharity.com/ambassadors/ |website=Overseas Plastic Surgery Appeal (OPSA)}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category-inline}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{cricinfo|ref=england/content/player/244497.html}}\n* {{cricketarchive|ref=Archive/Players/88/88341/88341.html}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070429164316/http://www.yorkshireccc.com/players/capped_first_eleven/adilrashid Player Profile and Statistics : Adil Rashid] from [[Yorkshire County Cricket Club]]\n\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title= England squads \n|bg= skyblue\n|fg= #000060\n|bordercolor=#000060\n|list1=\n{{England Squad 2011 Cricket World Cup}}\n{{England Squad 2019 Cricket World Cup}}\n}}\n{{Yorkshire squad}}\n{{South Australia 2010-11 KFC Twenty20 Big Bash Champions}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rashid, Adil}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English cricketers]]\n[[Category:Yorkshire cricketers]]\n[[Category:England Test cricketers]]\n[[Category:England One Day International cricketers]]\n[[Category:England Twenty20 International cricketers]]\n[[Category:English people of Pakistani descent]]\n[[Category:Cricketers from Bradford]]\n[[Category:Cricketers at the 2011 Cricket World Cup]]\n[[Category:Cricketers who have taken five wickets on Test debut]]\n[[Category:South Australia cricketers]]\n[[Category:Marylebone Cricket Club cricketers]]\n[[Category:British Asian cricketers]]\n[[Category:English people of Mirpuri descent]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople of Pakistani descent]]\n[[Category:British sportspeople of Pakistani descent]]\n[[Category:Adelaide Strikers cricketers]]\n[[Category:Dhaka Dynamites cricketers]]\n[[Category:Cricketers at the 2019 Cricket World Cup]]\n[[Category:English cricketers of the 21st century]]\n", "name_user": "157.36.58.106", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eBackground)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adil_Rashid"}
{"title_page": "Galveias", "text_new": "{{Infobox Portuguese subdivision\n|type = parish\n|official_name      = Galveias\n|image_skyline      = \n|image_caption      = \n|image_flag         =\n|image_shield       = PSR-galveias.png\n|image_location     = \n|region             = [[Alentejo]]\n|CIM                = [[Alto Alentejo (intermunicipal community)|Alto Alentejo]]\n|district           = [[Portalegre District|Portalegre]]\n|municipality       = [[Ponte de Sor]]\n|coordinates        = {{coord|39.160|-7.998|type:adm1st_region:PT_dim:50000|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation          = 224\n|area_total         = 79.83\n|population_as_of   = 2011\n|population_total   = 1061\n|patron             = [[Lawrence of Rome|S\u00e3o Louren\u00e7o]]\n|area_code          = 242 \n|postal_code        = 7400\n|website            = http://jfgalveias.pt/\n}}\n\n'''Galveias''' is a [[freguesia|civil parish]] in the municipality of [[Ponte de Sor Municipality|Ponte de Sor]], in the [[Portugal|Portuguese]] northern [[Alentejo]], district of [[Portalegre (district)|Portalegre]]. The population in 2011 was 1,061,<ref name=ine>[http://www.ine.pt/ngt_server/attachfileu.jsp?look_parentBoui=165404348&att_display=n&att_download=y Instituto Nacional de Estat\u00edstica (INE)], Census 2011 results according to the 2013 administrative division of Portugal</ref> in an area of 79.83&nbsp;km\u00b2.<ref name=dgt>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dgterritorio.pt/cartografia_e_geodesia/cartografia/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal_caop_/caop__download_/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal___versao_2017__em_vigor_/ |title=\u00c1reas das freguesias, concelhos, distritos e pa\u00eds |access-date=2018-11-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181105172426/http://www.dgterritorio.pt/cartografia_e_geodesia/cartografia/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal_caop_/caop__download_/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal___versao_2017__em_vigor_/ |archive-date=2018-11-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The small parish developed under the patronage of Order of Aviz, endowments from the Marqu\u00eas Rat\u00e3o family.\n\n==History==\nThe founding of this settlement is attributed to [[friar]] Louren\u00e7o Afonso, a master in the Order of Aviz, in 1342.<ref name=\"JFHistoria\">{{citation|editor=Junta Freguesia |publisher=Junta de Freguesia de Galveias |location=Galveias (Ponte de Sor), Portugal |year=2011 |access-date=20 September 2011 |language=Portuguese |title=Retalhos da Sua Hist\u00f3ria |url=http://www.jfgalveias.pt/historia.html |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402170510/http://www.jfgalveias.pt/historia.html |archive-date=2 April 2012 |df= }}</ref> Galveias was a [[priory]] in the Order of Avis, and benefited from the Order's wealth, and religious patronage.<ref name=JFHistoria/> But, economically, the region was already a prosperous agricultural centre, supported by the cultivation of oranges and raising of local poultry (both emblematic of its coat-of-arms).<ref name=JFHistoria/> It was originally known as Vila Nova do Laranjal because of its many orange groves. In addition, olive oil and wine (currently marketed under the Marques Rat\u00e3o brand) were produced and commercialized by its citizens.<ref name=JFHistoria/>\n\nJorge de Alencastre, son of King [[John II of Portugal|John II]], first expanded the settlement in 1425.\n\nOn 1 January 1512, the settlers benefited from a ''foral'' (''charter'') issued by the Aviz, and granted by King [[Manuel I of Portugal|Manuel I]]. By 1538, King John III elevated the settlement to the status of town.<ref name=JFHistoria/>\n\nImportant to the regions growth were the Counts of Galveias: the first titular, Dinis de Melo e Castro, was installed in 1691 (there were 10 titular until it was ultimately extinguished in 1940).<ref name=JFHistoria/>\n\n==Geography==\nGalveias is situated in the municipality of Ponte de Sor: it is located 14 kilometres from the municipal seat, and 18 kilometres from the town of Av\u00eds, crossed by the E.N.244 motorway.<ref name=JFHistoria/>\n\nThe local population is concentrated in the main town (Galveias), in which the homes are older dwellings, apart from two modern residential developments. Comprising 1800 residents, it is composed of primarily seniors (having the highest percentage of older adults), in addition to an elevated number of immigrants (primarily from the United Kingdom).\n\nGalveias has its own administrative council ({{lang-pt|Assembleia da Freguesia}}) and executive ({{lang-pt|Junta de Freguesia}}), post of the G.N.R, poste office and one banking institution. In addition to the kindergarten (''Escola EB/J D. Anita''), which receives 3 to 4 year oldes until primary, it also has its own primary school (''Escola de Galveias'') consisting of pre-primary, primary and pre-secondary students, consisting of six classrooms.\n\nA seniors residence provides lodging, assistance and hygiene for 70 seniors, supported by a small health centre ({{lang-pt|Centro de Sa\u00fade}}) providing administration, consultancy and curative care and a small hospital with limited assistance and palliative care.\n\n==Economy==\nThe region supports a micro-climate, adequate to support the orange groves, vineyards and olive orchards that dominate the agricultural industry. Portion of the parish is allocated to two hunting reserves for tourists and local huntsmen.\n\nMany of its citizens are involved in seasonal (agricultural) employment, work outside the parish (mainly in Ponte de Sor and Avis) or are employed under the ''Programas Ocupacionais do Centro de Emprego''. The commercial activities are limited, bu include caf\u00e9s and various smaller concessionaires.\n\n==Architecture==\n===Civic===\n* Building of Correios, Tel\u00e9grafos e Telefones (CTT) de Galveias\n* Building ''Largo da Miseric\u00f3rdia''\n* Fountain of Galveias ({{lang-pt|Chafariz de Galveias}})\n* Estate of the Bragas ({{lang-pt|Solar dos Bragas}})\n* Fountain of the Villa ({{lang-pt|Fonta da Villa}})\n* Galveias Health Care Centre ({{lang-pt|Posto Hospitalar Dr. M\u00e1rio Godinho de Campos/Centro de Sa\u00fade de Galveias}})\n* Galveias Kindergarten/D. Anita Kindergarten ({{lang-pt|Infant\u00e1rio da Junta de Freguesia de Galveias/Infant\u00e1rio Dona Anita}})\n* Galveias Primary School ({{lang-pt|Escola Prim\u00e1ria de Galveias}})\n* Parish Building ({{lang-pt|Junta Freguesia de Galveias}})\n* Residence EN224\n* Residence ''Rua da Miseric\u00f3rdia'', N\u00ba48\n* Residence ''Rua da Miseric\u00f3rdia'', N\u00ba55\n* Residence ''Rua da Miseric\u00f3rdia'', N\u00ba78\n* Residence ''Rua Joaquim Barradas de Carvalho'', N\u00ba61\n* Residence ''Rua M.M. Godinho de Campos''\n* Ribeira das Vinhas Primary School ({{lang-pt|Escola Prim\u00e1ria de Ribeira das Vinhas}})\n\n===Religious===\n* Chapel of the Santa Casa da Miseric\u00f3rdia ({{lang-pt|Capela da Santa Casa da Miseric\u00f3rdia de Galveias}}), or ''Funerary Chapel of Galveias'' ({{lang-pt|Capela Funer\u00e1ria de Galveias}})\n* Chapel of Santo Ant\u00f3nio ({{lang-pt|Capela de Santo Ant\u00f3nio}})\n* Chapel of S\u00e3o Jo\u00e3o ({{lang-pt|Capela de S\u00e3o Jo\u00e3o}})\n* Chapel of S\u00e3o Pedro ({{lang-pt|Capela de S\u00e3o Pedro}})\n* Chapel of S\u00e3o Saturnino ({{lang-pt|Capela de S\u00e3o Satunrino}})\n* Chapel of S\u00e3o Sebasti\u00e3o ({{lang-pt|Capela de S\u00e3o Sebasti\u00e3o}})\n* Chapel of Senhor das Almas ({{lang-pt|Capela do Senhora das Almas}})\n* Church of S\u00e3o Louren\u00e7ao ({{lang-pt|Igreja Matriz de Galveias/Igreja de S\u00e3o Louren\u00e7o}})\n\n==Culture==\nThe local cultural institutions include a public library (located in the old ''Casa do Povo''), the ''Casa da Cultura'' (''Culture House''), which also serves as a library, computer centre, music room, video centre, in addition to the presentation of socio-cultural events. There are also two halls to provide post-school services and extra-circular activities.\n\nThe ''Sociedade Filarm\u00f3nica'' is the historically popular local band, that provides concerts and play at most local events, as well as providing music classes for the region.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Parishes of Ponte de Sor}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Parishes of Ponte de Sor]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Portuguese subdivision\n|type = parish\n|official_name      = Galveias\n|image_skyline      = \n|image_caption      = \n|image_flag         =\n|image_shield       = PSR-galveias.png\n|image_location     = \n|region             = [[Alentejo]]\n|CIM                = [[Alto Alentejo (intermunicipal community)|Alto Alentejo]]\n|district           = [[Portalegre District|Portalegre]]\n|municipality       = [[Ponte de Sor]]\n|coordinates        = {{coord|39.160|-7.998|type:adm1st_region:PT_dim:50000|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation          = 224\n|area_total         = 79.83\n|population_as_of   = 2011\n|population_total   = 1061\n|patron             = [[Lawrence of Rome|S\u00e3o Louren\u00e7o]]\n|area_code          = 242 \n|postal_code        = 7400\n|website            = http://jfgalveias.pt/\n}}\n\n'''Galveias''' is a [[freguesia|civil parish]] in the municipality of [[Ponte de Sor Municipality|Ponte de Sor]], in the [[Portugal|Portuguese]] northern [[Alentejo]], district of [[Portalegre (district)|Portalegre]]. The population in 2011 was 1,061,<ref name=ine>[http://www.ine.pt/ngt_server/attachfileu.jsp?look_parentBoui=165404348&att_display=n&att_download=y Instituto Nacional de Estat\u00edstica (INE)], Census 2011 results according to the 2013 administrative division of Portugal</ref> in an area of 79.83&nbsp;km\u00b2.<ref name=dgt>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dgterritorio.pt/cartografia_e_geodesia/cartografia/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal_caop_/caop__download_/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal___versao_2017__em_vigor_/ |title=\u00c1reas das freguesias, concelhos, distritos e pa\u00eds |access-date=2018-11-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181105172426/http://www.dgterritorio.pt/cartografia_e_geodesia/cartografia/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal_caop_/caop__download_/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal___versao_2017__em_vigor_/ |archive-date=2018-11-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The small parish developed under the patronage of Order of Aviz, endowments from the Marqu\u00eas Rat\u00e3o family.\n\n==History==\nThe founding of this settlement is attributed to [[friar]] Louren\u00e7o Afonso, a master in the Order of Aviz, in 1342.<ref name=\"JFHistoria\">{{citation|editor=Junta Freguesia |publisher=Junta de Freguesia de Galveias |location=Galveias (Ponte de Sor), Portugal |year=2011 |access-date=20 September 2011 |language=Portuguese |title=Retalhos da Sua Hist\u00f3ria |url=http://www.jfgalveias.pt/historia.html |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402170510/http://www.jfgalveias.pt/historia.html |archive-date=2 April 2012 |df= }}</ref> Galveias was a [[priory]] in the Order of Avis, and benefited from the Order's wealth, and religious patronage.<ref name=JFHistoria/> But, economically, the region was already a prosperous agricultural centre, supported by the cultivation of oranges and raising of local poultry (both emblematic of its coat-of-arms).<ref name=JFHistoria/> It was originally known as Vila Nova do Laranjal because of its many orange groves. In addition, olive oil and wine (currently marketed under the Marques Rat\u00e3o brand) were produced and commercialized by its citizens.<ref name=JFHistoria/>\n\nJorge de Alencastre, son of King [[John II of Portugal|John II]], first expanded the settlement in 1425.\n\nOn 1 January 1512, the settlers benefited from a ''foral'' (''charter'') issued by the Aviz, and granted by King [[Manuel I of Portugal|Manuel I]]. By 1538, King John III elevated the settlement to the status of town.<ref name=JFHistoria/>\n\nImportant to the regions growth were the Counts of Galveias: the first titular, Dinis de Melo e Castro, was installed in 1691 (there were 10 titular until it was ultimately extinguished in 1940).<ref name=JFHistoria/>\n\n==Geography==\nGalveias is situated in the municipality of Ponte de Sor: it is located 14 kilometres from the municipal seat, and 18 kilometres from the town of Av\u00eds, crossed by the E.N.244 motorway.<ref name=JFHistoria/>\n\nThe local population is concentrated in the main town (Galveias), in which the homes are older dwellings, apart from two modern residential developments. Comprising 1800 residents, it is composed of primarily seniors (having the highest percentage of older adults), in addition to an elevated number of immigrants (primarily from the United Kingdom).\n\nGalveias has its own administrative council ({{lang-pt|Assembleia da Freguesia}}) and executive ({{lang-pt|Junta de Freguesia}}), post of the G.N.R, poste office and one banking institution. In addition to the kindergarten (''Escola EB/J D. Anita''), which receives 3 to 4 year oldes until primary, it also has its own primary school (''Escola de Galveias'') consisting of pre-primary, primary and pre-secondary students, consisting of six classrooms.\n\nA seniors residence provides lodging, assistance and hygiene for 70 seniors, supported by a small health centre ({{lang-pt|Centro de Sa\u00fade}}) providing administration, consultancy and curative care and a small hospital with limited assistance and palliative care.\n\n==Economy==\nThe region supports a micro-climate, adequate to support the orange groves, vineyards and olive orchards that dominate the agricultural industry. Portion of the parish is allocated to two hunting reserves for tourists and local huntsmen.\n\nMany of its citizens are involved in seasonal (agricultural) employment, work outside the parish (mainly in Ponte de Sor and Avis) or are employed under the ''Programas Ocupacionais do Centro de Emprego''. The commercial activities are limited, bu include caf\u00e9s and various smaller concessionaires.\n\n==Architecture==\n===Civic===\n* Building of Correios, Tel\u00e9grafos e Telefones (CTT) de Galveias\n* Building ''Largo da Miseric\u00f3rdia''\n* Fountain of Galveias ({{lang-pt|Chafariz de Galveias}})\n* Estate of the Bragas ({{lang-pt|Solar dos Bragas}})\n* Fountain of the Villa ({{lang-pt|Fonta da Villa}})\n* Galveias Health Care Centre ({{lang-pt|Posto Hospitalar Dr. M\u00e1rio Godinho de Campos/Centro de Sa\u00fade de Galveias}})\n* Galveias Kindergarten/D. Anita Kindergarten ({{lang-pt|Infant\u00e1rio da Junta de Freguesia de Galveias/Infant\u00e1rio Dona Anita}})\n* Galveias Primary School ({{lang-pt|Escola Prim\u00e1ria de Galveias}})\n* Parish Building ({{lang-pt|Junta Freguesia de Galveias}})\n* Residence EN224\n* Residence ''Rua da Miseric\u00f3rdia'', N\u00ba48\n* Residence ''Rua da Miseric\u00f3rdia'', N\u00ba55\n* Residence ''Rua da Miseric\u00f3rdia'', N\u00ba78\n* Residence ''Rua Joaquim Barradas de Carvalho'', N\u00ba61\n* Residence ''Rua M.M. Godinho de Campos''\n* Ribeira das Vinhas Primary School ({{lang-pt|Escola Prim\u00e1ria de Ribeira das Vinhas}})\n\n===Religious===\n* Chapel of the Santa Casa da Miseric\u00f3rdia ({{lang-pt|Capela da Santa Casa da Miseric\u00f3rdia de Galveias}}), or ''Funerary Chapel of Galveias'' ({{lang-pt|Capela Funer\u00e1ria de Galveias}})\n* Chapel of Santo Ant\u00f3nio ({{lang-pt|Capela de Santo Ant\u00f3nio}})\n* Chapel of S\u00e3o Jo\u00e3o ({{lang-pt|Capela de S\u00e3o Jo\u00e3o}})\n* Chapel of S\u00e3o Pedro ({{lang-pt|Capela de S\u00e3o Pedro}})\n* Chapel of S\u00e3o Saturnino ({{lang-pt|Capela de S\u00e3o Satunrino}})\n* Chapel of S\u00e3o Sebasti\u00e3o ({{lang-pt|Capela de S\u00e3o Sebasti\u00e3o}})\n* Chapel of Senhor das Almas ({{lang-pt|Capela do Senhora das Almas}})\n* Church of S\u00e3o Louren\u00e7ao ({{lang-pt|Igreja Matriz de Galveias/Igreja de S\u00e3o Louren\u00e7o}})\n\n==Culture==\nThe local cultural institutions include a public library (located in the old ''Casa do Povo''), the ''Casa da Cultura'' (''Culture House''), which also serves as a library, computer centre, music room, video centre, in addition to the presentation of socio-cultural events. There are also two halls to provide post-school services and extra-circular activities.\n\nThe ''Sociedade Filarm\u00f3nica'' is the historically popular local band, that provides concerts and play at most local events, as well as providing music classes for the region.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Parishes of Ponte de Sor}}\n\n[[Category:Parishes of Ponte de Sor]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Galveias"}
{"title_page": "James Edwards (basketball)", "text_new": "{{biased|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use American English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox NBA biography\n| name         = James Edwards\n| image        = James Edwards - Phoenix Suns.jpg\n| width        =\n| caption      = Edwards in 1987\n| position     = [[Center (basketball)|Center]] / [[Power forward (basketball)|Power forward]]\n| height_ft    = 7\n| height_in    = 1\n| weight_lb    = 225\n| number       = 42, 40, 53\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1955|11|22}}\n| birth_place  = [[Seattle, Washington]]\n| nationality  = American\n| high_school  = [[Roosevelt High School (Seattle, Washington)|Roosevelt]] (Seattle, Washington)\n| college      = [[Washington Huskies men's basketball|Washington]] (1973\u20131977)\n| draft_year   = 1977\n| draft_round  = 3\n| draft_pick   = 46\n| draft_team   = [[Los Angeles Lakers]]\n| career_start = 1977\n| career_end   = 1996\n| years1       = {{nbay|1977|start}}\n| team1        = [[Los Angeles Lakers]]\n| years2       = {{nbay|1977|start}}\u2013{{nbay|1980|end}}\n| team2        = [[Indiana Pacers]]\n| years3       = {{nbay|1981|start}}\u2013{{nbay|1982|end}}\n| team3        = [[Cleveland Cavaliers]]\n| years4       = {{nbay|1982|end}}\u2013{{nbay|1987|end}}\n| team4        = [[Phoenix Suns]]\n| years5       = {{nbay|1987|end}}\u2013{{nbay|1990|end}}\n| team5        = [[Detroit Pistons]]\n| years6       = {{nbay|1991|full=y}}\n| team6        = [[Los Angeles Clippers]]\n| years7       = {{nbay|1992|start}}\u2013{{nbay|1993|end}}\n| team7        = Los Angeles Lakers\n| years8       = {{nbay|1994|full=y}}\n| team8        = [[Portland Trail Blazers]]\n| years9       = {{nbay|1995|full=y}}\n| team9        = [[Chicago Bulls]]\n| highlights   = \n* 3\u00d7 [[List of NBA champions|NBA champion]] ([[1989 NBA Finals|1989]], [[1990 NBA Finals|1990]], [[1996 NBA Finals|1996]])\n* 2\u00d7 First-team [[List of All-Pac-12 Conference men's basketball teams|All-Pac-8]] (1976, 1977)\n| stats_league = NBA\n| stat1label   = [[Point (basketball)|Points]]\n| stat1value   = 14,862 (12.7 ppg)\n| stat2label   = [[Rebound (basketball)|Rebounds]]\n| stat2value   = 6,004 (5.1 rpg)\n| stat3label   = [[Block (basketball)|Blocks]]\n| stat3value   = 867 (0.7 bpg)\n| bbr          = edwarja01\n| letter       = e\n}}\n'''James Franklin Edwards''' (born November 22, 1955) is an American retired professional [[basketball]] player. Nicknamed \"[[Gautama Buddha|Buddha]]\" for his appearance (he often sported a [[Fu Manchu]] [[mustache]]) and stoic demeanor, the 7'1\" Edwards, though he never appeared in an [[National Basketball Association All-Star Game|All-Star Game]], was a reliable low-post scorer, averaging 12.7 points per game over his career.\n\nHe retired with 14,862 career points and 6,004 career rebounds.\n\n==Early years==\nBorn in [[Seattle, Washington]], Edwards starred at [[Roosevelt High School (Seattle)|Roosevelt High School]], where he led the Roughriders to the state title in 1973. He went on to play for the hometown [[Washington Huskies men's basketball|University of Washington]] Huskies under coach [[Marv Harshman]]. For his college career, between 1973 and 1977, Edwards averaged 14.6 points and 7.5 rebounds per game. James also called J-Boogie had tons a hoes!!! He also stole books from the book store and sold them back to the book store. James once quit in the middle of the game to go party on Beacon Hill. Later on he had this little shit of a daughter named Shakiana.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/players/james-edwards-1.html|title=James Edwards|website=[[Sports Reference]]|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== NBA career ==\nEdwards played 19 years (1977\u20131996) in the [[National Basketball Association]], playing both the [[Center (basketball)|center]] and [[Power forward (basketball)|power forward]] positions.\n\n=== Los Angeles Lakers ===\n\nEdwards was drafted by the [[Los Angeles Lakers]] on June 10, 1977 and made his NBA debut on October 18.\n<ref>https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/e/edwarja01.html</ref> He had a strong start to his rookie season, averaging 14.8 points and 7.2 rebounds before being traded later in the season.\n\n=== Indiana Pacers ===\nEdwards was then traded to the [[Indiana Pacers]] in 1977, where he enjoyed arguably his most productive statistical years. He averaged 15.9 points during his four years with the franchise.\n\n=== Cleveland Cavaliers ===\n\nEdwards spent parts of two seasons with the [[Cleveland Cavaliers]], averaging 16.0 points and 7.4 rebounds during his brief time there.\n\n=== Phoenix Suns ===\nEdwards was then traded to the [[Phoenix Suns]] in 1983, where he played for parts of six seasons. With the Suns he continued to be a key contributor, averaging 14.7 points and 5.6 rebounds per game.\n\n===Drug investigation===\n\nIn April of 1987, Edwards, along with [[Jay Humphries]] and [[Grant Gondrezick]], was indicted by a [[Maricopa County]], Arizona, grand jury investigating cocaine trafficking.  Edwards was indicted on three counts, conspiracy to possess a narcotic drug, conspiracy to transfer a narcotic drug, and conspiracy to transfer or possess marijuana <ref>https://www.nytimes.com/1987/04/18/sports/3-suns-players-are-indicted-in-drug-investigation.html</ref>.  Former Suns player [[Walter Davis (basketball)|Walter Davis]] was involved and was offered immunity in exchange for testimony, but his testimony failed to reveal critical details.  Edwards, along with all other defendants, never went to trial, but was required to undergo a drug counseling program as settlement <ref>http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1066773/1/index.htm</ref>.\n\n=== Detroit Pistons ===\n\nEdwards played four seasons with the [[Detroit Pistons]]. He was a key member of the 1989 and 1990 NBA [[NBA Finals|champion]] Detroit Pistons' Bad Boys squads, starting most of the team's games in 1990. He averaged 11.2 points and 3.6 rebounds as a Piston.\n\n=== Later career ===\n\nAfter his title runs with the Pistons, Edwards was traded to the [[Los Angeles Clippers]] before the 1991-92 season, where he spent one season. He then signed with the Lakers for a second stint, spending two seasons with the team that drafted him. This was followed by one season each of limited action with the [[Portland Trail Blazers]] and the [[Chicago Bulls]]. With the Bulls, Edwards won a third championship in the 19th and final season of his career in 1996, where he saw limited playing time off the bench.\n\n== NBA career statistics ==\n{{NBA player statistics legend|champion=y}}\n\n=== Regular season ===\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{Nbay|1977}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1977\u201378 Los Angeles Lakers season|L.A. Lakers]]\n| 25 || \u2013 || 28.9 || .459 || \u2013 || .640 || 7.2 || 1.2 || 0.6 || 1.1 || 14.8\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{Nbay|1977}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1977\u201378 Indiana Pacers season|Indiana]]\n| 58 || \u2013 || 29.0 || .450 || \u2013 || .649 || 7.5 || 1.0 || 0.6 || 0.9 || 15.4\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{Nbay|1978}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1978\u201379 Indiana Pacers season|Indiana]]\n| 82 || \u2013 || 31.0 || .501 || \u2013 || .676 || '''8.5''' || 1.1 || '''0.7''' || 1.3 || '''16.7'''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{Nbay|1979}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1979\u201380 Indiana Pacers season|Indiana]]\n| 82 || \u2013 || 28.2 || .512 || .000 || .681 || 7.0 || 1.5 || '''0.7''' || 1.3 || 15.7\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{Nbay|1980}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1980\u201381 Indiana Pacers season|Indiana]]\n| 81 || \u2013 || 29.3 || .509 || .000 || .703 || 7.0 || '''2.6''' || 0.4 || '''1.6''' || 15.6\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{Nbay|1981}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1981\u201382 Cleveland Cavaliers season|Cleveland]]\n| 77 || 75 || '''33.0''' || .511 || .000 ||