.750||0.7||0.0||0.0||0.0||1.8\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"2\"| Career\n| 111 || 33 || 19.9 || .468 || .000 || .682 || 3.2 || 0.8 || 0.2 || 0.4 || 9.3\n{{S-end}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of National Basketball Association players with 1000 games played]]\n*[[List of National Basketball Association seasons played leaders]]\n*[[List of oldest and youngest National Basketball Association players]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/e/edwarja01.html Career Stats]\n\n{{Detroit Pistons 1988-89 NBA champions}}\n{{Detroit Pistons 1989-90 NBA champions}}\n{{Chicago Bulls 1995-96 NBA champions}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Edwards, James}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American basketball players]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Basketball players from Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Centers (basketball)]]\n[[Category:Chicago Bulls players]]\n[[Category:Cleveland Cavaliers players]]\n[[Category:Detroit Pistons players]]\n[[Category:Indiana Pacers players]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles Clippers players]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles Lakers draft picks]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles Lakers players]]\n[[Category:Phoenix Suns players]]\n[[Category:Portland Trail Blazers players]]\n[[Category:Power forwards (basketball)]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Seattle]]\n[[Category:Washington Huskies men's basketball players]]\n", "text_old": "{{biased|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use American English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox NBA biography\n| name         = James Edwards\n| image        = James Edwards - Phoenix Suns.jpg\n| width        =\n| caption      = Edwards in 1987\n| position     = [[Center (basketball)|Center]] / [[Power forward (basketball)|Power forward]]\n| height_ft    = 7\n| height_in    = 1\n| weight_lb    = 225\n| number       = 42, 40, 53\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1955|11|22}}\n| birth_place  = [[Seattle, Washington]]\n| nationality  = American\n| high_school  = [[Roosevelt High School (Seattle, Washington)|Roosevelt]] (Seattle, Washington)\n| college      = [[Washington Huskies men's basketball|Washington]] (1973\u20131977)\n| draft_year   = 1977\n| draft_round  = 3\n| draft_pick   = 46\n| draft_team   = [[Los Angeles Lakers]]\n| career_start = 1977\n| career_end   = 1996\n| years1       = {{nbay|1977|start}}\n| team1        = [[Los Angeles Lakers]]\n| years2       = {{nbay|1977|start}}\u2013{{nbay|1980|end}}\n| team2        = [[Indiana Pacers]]\n| years3       = {{nbay|1981|start}}\u2013{{nbay|1982|end}}\n| team3        = [[Cleveland Cavaliers]]\n| years4       = {{nbay|1982|end}}\u2013{{nbay|1987|end}}\n| team4        = [[Phoenix Suns]]\n| years5       = {{nbay|1987|end}}\u2013{{nbay|1990|end}}\n| team5        = [[Detroit Pistons]]\n| years6       = {{nbay|1991|full=y}}\n| team6        = [[Los Angeles Clippers]]\n| years7       = {{nbay|1992|start}}\u2013{{nbay|1993|end}}\n| team7        = Los Angeles Lakers\n| years8       = {{nbay|1994|full=y}}\n| team8        = [[Portland Trail Blazers]]\n| years9       = {{nbay|1995|full=y}}\n| team9        = [[Chicago Bulls]]\n| highlights   = \n* 3\u00d7 [[List of NBA champions|NBA champion]] ([[1989 NBA Finals|1989]], [[1990 NBA Finals|1990]], [[1996 NBA Finals|1996]])\n* 2\u00d7 First-team [[List of All-Pac-12 Conference men's basketball teams|All-Pac-8]] (1976, 1977)\n| stats_league = NBA\n| stat1label   = [[Point (basketball)|Points]]\n| stat1value   = 14,862 (12.7 ppg)\n| stat2label   = [[Rebound (basketball)|Rebounds]]\n| stat2value   = 6,004 (5.1 rpg)\n| stat3label   = [[Block (basketball)|Blocks]]\n| stat3value   = 867 (0.7 bpg)\n| bbr          = edwarja01\n| letter       = e\n}}\n'''James Franklin Edwards''' (born November 22, 1955) is an American retired professional [[basketball]] player. Nicknamed \"[[Gautama Buddha|Buddha]]\" for his appearance (he often sported a [[Fu Manchu]] [[mustache]]) and stoic demeanor, the 7'1\" Edwards, though he never appeared in an [[National Basketball Association All-Star Game|All-Star Game]], was a reliable low-post scorer, averaging 12.7 points per game over his career.\n\nHe retired with 14,862 career points and 6,004 career rebounds.\n\n==Early years==\nBorn in [[Seattle, Washington]], Edwards starred at [[Roosevelt High School (Seattle)|Roosevelt High School]], where he led the Roughriders to the state title in 1973. He went on to play for the hometown [[Washington Huskies men's basketball|University of Washington]] Huskies under coach [[Marv Harshman]]. For his college career, between 1973 and 1977, Edwards averaged 14.6 points and 7.5 rebounds per game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/players/james-edwards-1.html|title=James Edwards|website=[[Sports Reference]]|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== NBA career ==\nEdwards played 19 years (1977\u20131996) in the [[National Basketball Association]], playing both the [[Center (basketball)|center]] and [[Power forward (basketball)|power forward]] positions.\n\n=== Los Angeles Lakers ===\n\nEdwards was drafted by the [[Los Angeles Lakers]] on June 10, 1977 and made his NBA debut on October 18.\n<ref>https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/e/edwarja01.html</ref> He had a strong start to his rookie season, averaging 14.8 points and 7.2 rebounds before being traded later in the season.\n\n=== Indiana Pacers ===\nEdwards was then traded to the [[Indiana Pacers]] in 1977, where he enjoyed arguably his most productive statistical years. He averaged 15.9 points during his four years with the franchise.\n\n=== Cleveland Cavaliers ===\n\nEdwards spent parts of two seasons with the [[Cleveland Cavaliers]], averaging 16.0 points and 7.4 rebounds during his brief time there.\n\n=== Phoenix Suns ===\nEdwards was then traded to the [[Phoenix Suns]] in 1983, where he played for parts of six seasons. With the Suns he continued to be a key contributor, averaging 14.7 points and 5.6 rebounds per game.\n\n===Drug investigation===\n\nIn April of 1987, Edwards, along with [[Jay Humphries]] and [[Grant Gondrezick]], was indicted by a [[Maricopa County]], Arizona, grand jury investigating cocaine trafficking.  Edwards was indicted on three counts, conspiracy to possess a narcotic drug, conspiracy to transfer a narcotic drug, and conspiracy to transfer or possess marijuana <ref>https://www.nytimes.com/1987/04/18/sports/3-suns-players-are-indicted-in-drug-investigation.html</ref>.  Former Suns player [[Walter Davis (basketball)|Walter Davis]] was involved and was offered immunity in exchange for testimony, but his testimony failed to reveal critical details.  Edwards, along with all other defendants, never went to trial, but was required to undergo a drug counseling program as settlement <ref>http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1066773/1/index.htm</ref>.\n\n=== Detroit Pistons ===\n\nEdwards played four seasons with the [[Detroit Pistons]]. He was a key member of the 1989 and 1990 NBA [[NBA Finals|champion]] Detroit Pistons' Bad Boys squads, starting most of the team's games in 1990. He averaged 11.2 points and 3.6 rebounds as a Piston.\n\n=== Later career ===\n\nAfter his title runs with the Pistons, Edwards was traded to the [[Los Angeles Clippers]] before the 1991-92 season, where he spent one season. He then signed with the Lakers for a second stint, spending two seasons with the team that drafted him. This was followed by one season each of limited action with the [[Portland Trail Blazers]] and the [[Chicago Bulls]]. With the Bulls, Edwards won a third championship in the 19th and final season of his career in 1996, where he saw limited playing time off the bench.\n\n== NBA career statistics ==\n{{NBA player statistics legend|champion=y}}\n\n=== Regular season ===\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{Nbay|1977}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1977\u201378 Los 